# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: laurelton-queens
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] The **2000 United States census**, conducted by the Census Bureau, determined the resident population of the United States on April 1, 2000, to be 281,421,906, an increase of 13.2 percent over the 248,709,873 people enumerated during the 1990 census.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] This was the twenty-second federal census and was at the time the largest civilly administered peacetime effort in the United States.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Approximately 16 percent of households received a "long form" of the 2000 census, which contained over 100 questions.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] It would be the last census to include the "long form", since subsequent censuses, starting with the 2010 census, would be "short form" only, with the more detailed questions being replaced by the new American Community Survey.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Full documentation on the 2000 census, including census forms and a procedural history, is available from the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] This was the first census in which a state—California—recorded a population of over 30 million, as well as the first in which two states—California and Texas—recorded populations of more than 20 million.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Microdata from the 2000 census is freely available through the Integrated Public Use Microdata Series.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Aggregate data for small areas, together with electronic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Personally identifiable information will be available in 2072.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] The U.S. resident population includes the total number of people in the 50 states and the District of Columbia.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] The Bureau also enumerated the residents of the U.S. territory of Puerto Rico; its population was 3,808,610, an 8.1% increase over the number from a decade earlier.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Regionally, the South and West experienced the bulk of the nation's population increase: 14,790,890 and 10,411,850, respectively.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] This meant that the mean center of U.S. population moved to Phelps County, Missouri.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] The Northeastern United States grew by 2,785,149; the Midwest by 4,724,144.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] The results of the census are used to determine how many congressional districts each state is apportioned.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Congress defines the formula, in accordance with Title 2 of the U.S.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Code, to reapportion among the states the 435 seats in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] The apportionment population consists of the resident population of the fifty states, plus the overseas military and federal civilian employees and their dependents living with them who could be allocated to a state.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Each member of the House represents a population of about 647,000.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] The populations of the District of Columbia and Puerto Rico are excluded from the apportionment population because they do not have voting seats in the U.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Since the first census in 1790, the decennial count has been the basis for the United States representative form of government.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Article I, Section II specifies that "The Number of Representatives shall not exceed one for every thirty Thousand, but each State shall have at Least one Representative." In 1790, each member of the House represented about 34,000 residents.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Since then, the House more than quadrupled in size, and in 1911 the number of representatives was fixed at 435.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Today, each member represents about 20 times as many constituents.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] In the years leading up to the 2000 census, there was substantial controversy over whether the Bureau should adjust census figures based on a follow-up survey, called the post-enumeration survey, of a sample of blocks.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] This recommendation was followed by the Secretary of Commerce (the official in charge of making the determination).
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] After the census was tabulated, Utah challenged the results in two different ways.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Utah was extremely close to gaining a fourth congressional seat, falling 857 people short, which in turn was allocated to North Carolina.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] The margin was later shortened to 80 people, after the federal government discovered that it overcounted the population of North Carolina by 2,673 residents.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] The Census Bureau counted members of the military and other federal civilian employees serving abroad as residents of their home state but did not count other people living outside the United States.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Utah claimed that people traveling abroad as religious missionaries should be counted as residents and that the failure to do so imposed a burden on Mormon religious practice.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Almost half of all Mormon missionaries, more than 11,000 people, were from Utah; only 102 came from North Carolina.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] If this policy were changed, then Utah would have received an additional seat instead of North Carolina.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] On November 26, 2002, the Supreme Court affirmed the lower court ruling that rejected Utah's efforts to have Mormon missionaries counted.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] The state of Utah then filed another lawsuit alleging that the statistical methods used in computing the state populations were improper and cost Utah the seat.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] The Bureau uses a method called imputation to assign a number of residents to addresses where residents cannot be reached after multiple efforts.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] While nationwide the imputation method added 0.4% to the population, the rate in Utah was 0.2%.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] The state challenged that the use of imputation violates the Census Act of 1957 and that it also fails the Constitution's requirement in Article I, Section 2 that an "actual enumeration" be used for apportionment.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Evans*, made it to the Supreme Court, but Utah was again defeated.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] The census forms did not include any questions regarding sexual orientation, making it impossible to compile data comparing heterosexual and homosexual populations.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] However, two questions *were* asked that allowed same-sex partnerships to be counted.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] The questionnaires asked the sex of each person in a household and they asked what the relationship was between each of the members of the household.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Respondents could check "Husband/wife" or "unmarried partner" or a number of other relationships.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Responses were tabulated and the Census Bureau reported that there were more than 658,000 same-sex couples heading households in the United States.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] However, only about 25% of gay men and 40% of lesbians are in shared-household partnerships at any one time, according to non-census surveys.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] For every same-sex couple tallied in the census, there could be three to six more homosexual un-partnered individuals who would not be counted as gay.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] The census reported that same-sex male couples numbered 336,001 and female same-sex couples numbered 329,522.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Extrapolating from those figures and the surveyed partnering habits of homosexuals, as many as 4.3 million homosexual adults could have been living in the U.S. in 2000.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] The exact number cannot be known because the census did not count them specifically.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Bisexual and transgender populations were not counted, either, because there were no questions regarding this information.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Also unavailable is the number of additional same-sex couples living under the same roof as the first, though this applies to additional heterosexual couples as well.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] The lack of accurate numbers makes it difficult for lawmakers who are considering legislation on hate crimes or social services for gay families with children.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] It also makes for less accuracy when predicting the fertility of a population.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Another issue that concerned gay rights advocates involved the automatic changing of data during the tabulation process.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] This automatic software data compiling method, called *allocation*, was designed to counteract mistakes and discrepancies in returned questionnaires.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] Forms that were filled out by two same-sex persons who checked the "Husband/wife" relationship box were treated as a discrepancy.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] The Census Bureau explained that same-sex "Husband/wife" data samples were changed to "unmarried partner" by computer processing methods in 99% of the cases.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] In the remaining 1%, computer systems used one of two possibilities: a) one of the two listed sexes was changed, making the partnership appear heterosexual, or b) if the two partners were more than 15 years apart in age, they might have been reassigned into a familial parent/child relationship.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] The process of automatic reassignment of same-sex marriage data was initiated so that the Census Bureau would not contravene the Defense of Marriage Act passed in 1996.
[src:laurelton-queens/2000-united-states-census] With allocation moving married same-sex couples to the unmarried partner category, social scientists lost information that could have been extracted relating to the social stability of a same-gender couple who identify themselves as married.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The **2010 United States census** was the 23rd United States census.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] National Census Day, the reference day used for the census, was April 1, 2010.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The census was taken via mail-in citizen self-reporting, with enumerators serving to spot-check randomly selected neighborhoods and communities.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] As part of a drive to increase the count's accuracy, 635,000 temporary enumerators were hired.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The population of the United States was counted as 308,745,538, a 9.7% increase from the 2000 United States census.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] This was the first census in which all states recorded a population of over 500,000 people as well as the first in which all 100 largest cities recorded populations of over 200,000.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] It was the first census since 1930 that California did not record the largest population growth in absolute number.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Texas surpassed California's growth by 4.3 million to 3.4 million.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] As required by the United States Constitution, the U.S.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Census has been conducted every 10 years since 1790.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The 2000 U.S. census was the previous census completed.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Census is required by law of people living in the United States in Title 13 of the United States Code.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] On January 25, 2010, Census Bureau Director Robert Groves personally inaugurated the 2010 census enumeration by counting World War II veteran Clifton Jackson, a resident of Noorvik, Alaska.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] More than 120 million census forms were delivered by the U.S.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The number of forms mailed out or hand-delivered by the Census Bureau was approximately 134 million on April 1, 2010.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 census national mail participation rate was 74%.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] From April through July 2010, census takers visited households that did not return a form, an operation called "non-response follow-up" (NRFU).
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau delivered population information to the U.S. president for apportionment, and later in March 2011, complete redistricting data was delivered to states.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Personally identifiable information will be available in 2082.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The Census Bureau did not use a long form for the 2010 census.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] In several previous censuses, one in six households received this long form, which asked for detailed social and economic information.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Were there any additional people staying here on April 1, 2010, that you did not include in Question 1?
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] What is Person 1's age and Person 1's date of birth?
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Is Person 1 of Hispanic, Latino, or Spanish origin?
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Does Person 1 sometimes live or stay somewhere else?
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The form included space to repeat some or all of these questions for up to twelve residents total.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] In contrast to the 2000 census, an Internet response option was not offered, nor was the form available for download.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Detailed socioeconomic information collected during past censuses will continue to be collected through the American Community Survey.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The survey provides data about communities in the United States on a 1-year or 3-year cycle, depending on the size of the community, rather than once every 10 years.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] A small percentage of the population on a rotating basis will receive the survey each year, and no household will receive it more than once every five years.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau announced that it would count same-sex married couples.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] However, the final form did not contain a separate "same-sex married couple" option.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] When noting the relationship between household members, same-sex couples who are married could mark their spouses as being "Husband or wife", the same response given by opposite-sex married couples.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] An "unmarried partner" option was available for couples (whether same-sex or opposite-sex) who were not married.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The Census 2010 Language Program was significantly expanded.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Language assistance in 49 languages in the 2000 Census was increased to 59 languages in Census 2000.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] In addition to English, Census questionnaire was available in five non-English languages: Spanish, Chinese (simplified), Korean, Vietnamese, and Russian.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 census cost $13 billion, approximately $42 per capita; by comparison, the 2010 census per-capita cost for China was about US$1 and for India was US$0.40.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Operational costs were $5.4 billion, significantly under the $7 billion budget.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] In December 2010 the Government Accountability Office (GAO) noted that the cost of conducting the census has approximately doubled each decade since 1970.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] In a detailed 2004 report to Congress, the GAO called on the Census Bureau to address cost and design issues, and at that time, had estimated the 2010 census cost to be $11 billion.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Locke credited the management practices of Census Bureau director Robert Groves, citing in particular the decision to buy additional advertising in locations where responses lagged, which improved the overall response rate.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The agency also has begun to rely more on questioning neighbors or other reliable third parties when a person could not be immediately reached at home, which reduced the cost of follow-up visits.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Census data for about 22% of U.S. households that did not reply by mail were based on such outside interviews, Groves said.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] In 2005, Lockheed Martin won a six-year, $500 million contract to capture and standardize data for the census.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The contract included systems, facilities, and staffing.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The final value of that contract was in excess of one billion dollars.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Information technology was about a quarter of the projected $11.3 billion cost of the decennial census.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The use of high-speed document scanning technology, such as ImageTrac scanners developed by IBML, helped Lockheed Martin complete the project on schedule and under budget.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Due to the rise in social media and cell-phone usage in the U.S., the Census Bureau used research gathered through a cell-phone study in order to target media and ads to populations that were nonrespondents and promote census participation.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] This study also helped gauge the mindset of those who fail to respond, trying to figure out why.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] This was the first census to use hand-held computing devices with GPS capability, although they were only used for the address canvassing operation.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Enumerators (information gatherers) that had operational problems with the device understandably made negative reports.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] During the 2009 Senate confirmation hearings for Robert Groves, President Obama's Census Director appointee, there was much mention of contracting problems but very little criticism of the units themselves.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The Census Bureau chose to conduct the primary operation, Non-Response Follow Up (NRFU), without using the handheld computing devices.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] There was a penalty of $100 for not completing some or all of the 2010 U.S.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau director Robert Grove, however, wrote "the Census Bureau has rarely prosecuted failure to respond.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] While the rationale for the mandatory nature of the census still applies today, our message for the 2010 Census is about the common good benefits of participation".
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The fine for non-participation is much lower than that for reporting false information.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The Association of Community Organizations for Reform Now (ACORN) was given a contract to help publicize the importance of the census count and to encourage individuals to fill out their forms.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] In September 2009, after controversial undercover videos showing four ACORN staffers giving tax advice to a man and a woman posing as a prostitute, the bureau canceled ACORN's contract.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Various American celebrities, including Demi Lovato and Eva Longoria, were used in public service announcements targeting younger people to fill out census forms.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Wilmer Valderrama and Rosario Dawson have helped spread census awareness among young Hispanics, a historically low participating ethnicity in the U.S. census.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Rapper Ludacris also participated in efforts to spread awareness of the 2010 census.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The Census Bureau hired about 635,000 people to find those U.S. residents who had not returned their forms by mail; as of May 28, 2010, 113 census workers had been victims of crime while conducting the census.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Some political conservatives and libertarians questioned the validity of the questions and even encouraged people to refuse to answer questions for privacy and constitutional reasons.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] As a result, the Census Bureau undertook an unprecedented advertising campaign targeted at encouraging white political conservatives to fill out their forms, in the hope of avoiding an undercount of this group.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 U.S. census was the primary sponsor at NASCAR races in Atlanta, Bristol, and Martinsville, and sponsored the No.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] 16 Ford Fusion driven by Greg Biffle for part of the season, because of a marketing survey that indicated most NASCAR fans lean politically conservative.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] It also ran an advertisement during the 2010 Super Bowl, and hired singer Marie Osmond, who is thought to have many conservative fans, to publicize the census.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The results of the 2010 census determined the number of seats that each state received in the United States House of Representatives starting with the 2012 elections.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Consequently, this affected the number of votes each state had in the Electoral College for the 2012 presidential election.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Because of population changes, eighteen states had changes in their number of seats.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Eight states gained at least one seat, and ten states lost at least one seat.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The final result involved 12 seats being switched.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Some objected to the counting of persons who are in the United States illegally.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Senators David Vitter (R-LA) and Bob Bennett (R-UT) tried unsuccessfully to add questions on immigration status to the census form.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Organizations such as the Prison Policy Initiative argued that the census counts of incarcerated men and women as residents of prisons, rather than of their pre-incarceration addresses, skewed political clout and resulted in misleading demographic and population data.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Many residents of prisons counted on the 2010 census were those who identify as Black and Hispanic.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] This could lead to the loss of resources for underserved minority communities.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The term "Negro" was used in the questionnaire as one of the options for African Americans (Question 9.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Black, African Am., or Negro) as a choice to describe one's race.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Census Bureau spokesman Jack Martin explained that "many older African-Americans identified themselves that way, and many still do.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Those who identify themselves as Negroes need to be included." The word was also used in the 2000 census, with over 56,000 people identifying themselves as "Negro".
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] In response to complaints over the word's inclusion on the 2010 census, the Census Bureau announced in 2013 that it would stop using "Negro" going forward, with the 2014 American Community Survey census form being the first without the word.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The 2010 census contained ten questions about age, gender, ethnicity, home ownership, and household relationships.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Six of the ten questions were to be answered for each individual in the household.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Federal law has provisions for fining those who refuse to complete the census form.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Detroit Mayor Dave Bing held a press conference on March 22, 2011, to announce that the city would challenge its census results.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The challenge, being led by the city's planning department, cited an inconsistency as an example showing a downtown census tract which lost only 60 housing units, but 1,400 people, implying that a downtown jail or dormitory was missed in canvassing.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] NYC Mayor Michael Bloomberg held a conference on March 27, 2011, to announce that the city would also challenge his city's census results, specifically the apparent undercounting in the boroughs of Queens and Brooklyn.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Bloomberg said that the numbers for Queens and Brooklyn, the two most populous boroughs, are implausible.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] According to the census, they grew by only 0.1% and 1.6%, respectively, while the other boroughs grew by between 3% and 5%.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] He also stated that the census showed improbably high numbers of vacant housing in vital neighborhoods such as Jackson Heights, Queens.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The District of Columbia announced in August 2011 that it would also challenge its census results.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The Mayor's Office claimed that the detailed information provided for 549 census blocks is "nonsensical", listing examples of census data that show housing units located in the middle of a street that does not actually exist.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] However, officials do not believe the city's total population will drastically change as a result of the challenge.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The state with the highest percentage rate of growth was Nevada, while the state with the largest population increase was Texas.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] Michigan, the 8th largest by population, was the only state to lose population (although Puerto Rico, a U.S. territory, lost population as well), and the District of Columbia saw its first gain since the 1950s.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] The resident populations listed below do not include people living overseas.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] For Congressional apportionment, the sum of a state's resident population and its population of military personnel and federal contractors living overseas (but not other citizens overseas, such as missionaries or expatriate workers) is used.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] These are core metropolitan rankings versus combined statistical areas.
[src:laurelton-queens/2010-united-states-census] For full list with current data, go to metropolitan statistics.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The small western enclave of **Addisleigh Park** is a U.S. historic district where many notable African Americans have lived, including Jackie Robinson, W.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Du Bois, Lena Horne, and many jazz musicians such as Fats Waller, Ella Fitzgerald and Count Basie.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans is located in Queens Community District 12 and its ZIP Code is 11412.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] It is patrolled by the New York City Police Department's 113th Precinct.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans is represented by the New York City Council's 27th and 28th Districts.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Part of a land grant to Dutch settlers from New Netherland Governor Peter Stuyvesant in 1655, the area, like much of Queens, remained farmland and forest for most of the next two centuries.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] By the 1800s, the lands of four families—the Remsens, Everitts, Ludlums, and Hendricksons—formed the nucleus of this sprawling farm community in the eastern portion of the Town of Jamaica.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] In 1852, the old mill pond that is now at the center of Baisley Pond Park was acquired by the Brooklyn waterworks for use as a reservoir.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] In 1872, the Long Island Rail Road's Cedarhurst Cut-off was built through the area, but no stop appears on the first timetables.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] In 1892, an area called Francis Farm was surveyed and developed for housing.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] There were numerous Francis families farming in the eastern portion of the Town of Jamaica in the 1880s.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Francis Lewis Boulevard (named for a signer of the Declaration of Independence, from Queens), which does not yet appear on maps from 1909, nor in 1910, is now the eastern boundary of St.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Soon, the first street lights illuminated the crossroads that is now Linden Boulevard and Farmers Boulevard.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] New shops clustered around August Everitt's lone store.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans Long Island Rail Road station opened where the tracks crossed Locust Avenue (now Baisley Boulevard).
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The station was razed and replaced with the current, grade separated station on October 15, 1935.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] In 1899, a year after Queens became part of New York City (and with the Town of Jamaica and the Village of Jamaica thereby dissolved), the new post office for the 600 residents was named St.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans, after St Albans in Hertfordshire, England, which itself was named after a Saint Alban, thought to be the first Christian martyred in England.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The name had been in use for the area since at least 1894 for the name of the school district, and the LIRR station was named St.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] A 1909 map also shows a St Albans Avenue and a St Albans Place in the area.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The site was originally occupied by the St.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans Golf Course and Country Club, which was completed in 1915.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The club brought rich and famous golfers, including baseball star Babe Ruth, and hosted the 1930 Metropolitan Amateur.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The Depression forced the golf course owners to try to sell, but plans for private development fell through.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The land was seized by the federal government in 1942, and construction soon began on the St.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans Naval Hospital, which opened in 1943.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] After construction was completed in 1950, the hospital had 3000 beds and contained a network of 76 wards.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The hospital was turned over to the Veterans Administration in 1974, reopening as a VA hospital two years later, and more recently evolved into the Veterans Administration St.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans Primary and Extended Care Facility.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] A portion of the hospital site became Roy Wilkins Park in the 1980s.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans is the small western enclave of Addisleigh Park, a U.S. historic district that consists of single-family homes built in a variety of styles between the 1910s and 1930s.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Though originally intended as a segregated community for white people only, from the late 1930s many notable African Americans have lived there.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Today, it remains a predominantly African American and Jamaican enclave that is more upscale than surrounding areas in southeast Queens.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Between 1900 and 1940, the village of Addisleigh Park was developed by a handful of eminent white entrepreneurs including Edwin H.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Restrictive covenants were established to prohibit the sale of any of its properties to blacks.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] A 1926 *New York Times* article insists, "Addisleigh, together with the St.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans Golf Club, was laid out under the personal direction of Edwin H.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Brown, and carries a land and house restriction of the highest type." Two lawsuits were filed successfully by white residents who accused their neighbors of breaking the contractual segregation imposed on the neighborhood by its developers.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Addisleigh Park boasted well-kept rows of Tudor and Colonial homes.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The neighborhood's close proximity to Manhattan allowed for quick and frequent commuting.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] During the Swing Era, Manhattan's 52nd Street served as the epicenter of Swing Era live entertainment and musical innovation.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] For this reason, many successful African American jazz musicians began to recognize Addisleigh Park as the newest suburban haven for wealthy, influential artists.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Kraemer,* the United States Supreme Court ruled that racially restrictive covenants violated the equal-protection clause of the 14th Amendment, though by that year, Addisleigh Park had already become a haven for world-famous African Americans in jazz and sports.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The neighborhood was declared a historic district by the NYC Landmarks Preservation Commission in 2011.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Based on data from the 2010 United States census, the population of St.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Covering an area of 1,778.68 acres (719.81 ha), the neighborhood had a population density of 27.3 inhabitants per acre (17,500/sq mi; 6,700/km2).
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 6.5% (3,146) of the population.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The entirety of Community Board 12, which mainly comprises Jamaica but also includes St.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans and Hollis, had 232,911 inhabitants as of NYC Health's 2018 Community Health Profile, with an average life expectancy of 80.5 years.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] This is slightly lower than the median life expectancy of 81.2 for all New York City neighborhoods.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Most inhabitants are youth and middle-aged adults: 22% are between the ages of between 0–17, 27% between 25 and 44, and 27% between 45 and 64.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The ratio of college-aged and elderly residents was lower, at 10% and 14% respectively.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] As of 2017, the median household income in Community Board 12 was $61,670.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans and Jamaica residents lived in poverty, compared to 19% in all of Queens and 20% in all of New York City.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] One in eight residents (12%) were unemployed, compared to 8% in Queens and 9% in New York City.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Rent burden, or the percentage of residents who have difficulty paying their rent, is 56% in St.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans and Jamaica, higher than the boroughwide and citywide rates of 53% and 51% respectively.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Based on this calculation, as of 2018, St.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans and Jamaica are considered to be high-income relative to the rest of the city and not gentrifying.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans housing consists mostly of detached, one and two-family homes.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Linden Boulevard is the major shopping street.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] In 2011 *The New York Times* reported that many foreclosures were occurring and there was a high level of unemployment.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] At that time, many black people were moving from St.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans are patrolled by the NYPD's 113th Precinct, located at 167-02 Baisley Boulevard.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The 113th Precinct ranked 55th safest out of 69 patrol areas for per-capita crime in 2010.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] But the precinct crime rate is much lower than in 1990, all categories having decreased by 86.1% between 1990 and 2018.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The precinct reported 5 murders, 28 rapes, 156 robberies, 383 felony assaults, 153 burglaries, 414 grand larcenies, and 138 grand larcenies auto in 2018.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] As of 2018, preterm births and births to teenage mothers are more common in St.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans and Jamaica than in other places citywide.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans and Jamaica, there were 10 preterm births per 1,000 live births (compared to 87 per 1,000 citywide), and 21.4 births to teenage mothers per 1,000 live births (compared to 19.3 per 1,000 citywide).
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans and Jamaica have a low population of residents who are uninsured.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] In 2018, this population of uninsured residents was estimated to be 5%, lower than the citywide rate of 12%.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The concentration of fine particulate matter, the deadliest type of air pollutant, in St.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans and Jamaica is 0.007 milligrams per cubic metre (7.0×10−9 oz/ft3), less than the city average.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans and Jamaica residents are smokers, which is lower than the city average of 14% of residents being smokers.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans and Jamaica, 30% of residents are obese, 16% are diabetic, and 37% have high blood pressure—compared to the citywide averages of 22%, 8%, and 23% respectively.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] In addition, 23% of children are obese, compared to the citywide average of 20%.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Eighty-six percent of residents eat some fruits and vegetables every day, which is slightly less than the city's average of 87%.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] In 2018, 82% of residents described their health as "good", "very good", or "excellent", higher than the city's average of 78%.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans and Jamaica, there are 20 bodegas.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The nearest major hospitals are Jamaica Hospital and Queens Hospital Center, both located in Jamaica.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans is covered by the ZIP Code 11412.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The United States Post Office operates two post offices nearby: the Saint Albans Station at 195-04 Linden Boulevard and the Rochdale Village Station at 165-100 Baisley Boulevard.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans, operated by the New York City Department of Parks and Recreation.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans Park is bounded by Merrick Boulevard, Sayres Avenue, and Marne Place.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] It includes facilities for cricket, handball, and tennis, as well as fitness equipment, playground, and spray showers.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The land was acquired by the city for use as a park in 1914, and it was slightly expanded in 1968.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Roy Wilkins Park is located between 115th Avenue and Merrick and Baisley Boulevards.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] It contains facilities for baseball, basketball, cricket, handball, swimming, tennis, and track-and-field, as well as a recreation center, fitness equipment, playground, and spray showers.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The land, formerly a naval hospital, was given to the city in 1977.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] It is named for civil rights activist Roy Wilkins.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Railroad Park, a nature area, is located on a triangular plot bounded by 129th Avenue, 176th Street, and the Long Island Rail Road's Atlantic Branch.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The land for this park was acquired in 1962–1963.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] O'Connell Playground is located between Murdock Avenue, 112th Road, and 197th and 198th Street.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] It contains basketball and handball courts, fitness equipment, a play area, and spray showers.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The playground is named for World War I veteran Daniel M.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The Liberty Rock is a symbol of the history and culture of the African American community in St.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The painting of the rock in red, black, and green, the colors of the Pan-African flag, represents the community's commitment to civil rights, group identity, and fostering ties between all people of African descent.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The location of the rock, at the intersection of St.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans and Hollis neighborhoods in Jamaica, highlights its significance as a shared symbol for the entire community.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The Liberty Rock serves as a symbol of resistance and resilience, reminding the community of its rich cultural heritage and ongoing struggle for equality and justice.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans and Jamaica generally have a lower rate of college-educated residents than the rest of the city as of 2018.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] While 29% of residents age 25 and older have a college education or higher, 19% have less than a high school education and 51% are high school graduates or have some college education.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] By contrast, 39% of Queens residents and 43% of city residents have a college education or higher.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans and Jamaica students excelling in math rose from 36% in 2000 to 55% in 2011, and reading achievement increased slightly from 44% to 45% during the same time period.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans and Jamaica's rate of elementary school student absenteeism is more than the rest of New York City.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans and Jamaica, 22% of elementary school students missed twenty or more days per school year, higher than the citywide average of 20%.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Additionally, 74% of high school students in St.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans and Jamaica graduate on time, about the same as the citywide average of 75%.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Public schools are operated by the New York City Department of Education (NYCDOE).
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Eagle Academy for Young Men III, a combined public middle and high school, serves grades 6–12.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] The Queens Public Library operates the St.Albans branch at 191-05 Linden Boulevard.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Numerous MTA bus lines run through the neighborhood, including the Q3, Q4, Q5, Q42, Q51, Q77, Q83, Q84, Q85, Q86, Q87, Q89, QM63, and QM64 all of which connect to the New York City Subway and the Long Island Rail Road (LIRR) at Jamaica Center and Jamaica, respectively.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Albans was home to many artists of the jazz, hip hop, and rap music genres.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Famous stride pianist Fats Waller was the first well-known musician to move into Addisleigh Park at the peak of his career in the late 1930s.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Waller had grown up in the Church (his father was a pastor).
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] He subsequently had his home in Addisleigh Park fashioned with a built-in Hammond organ.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] He died in 1943 from bronchial pneumonia.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] In 1937, jazz pianist and bandleader Count Basie moved his orchestra from Kansas City to New York.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Count Basie's orchestra performed at world-famous Manhattan venues including the Roseland Ballroom, the Savoy Ballroom, and the Woodside Hotel.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] In 1946, Basie and his wife, Katy, bought a home in Addisleigh Park, where the couple lived until 1973 when it was sold to bandleader/singer/pianist, Robert (Bubber) Johnson.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Singer, film actress, and Civil Rights Activist Lena Horne also moved into the Addisleigh Park neighborhood in the year 1946.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Soon after Horne, jazz trumpeter and bandleader Mercer Ellington, son of jazz great Duke Ellington, moved into Addisleigh Park in 1948.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Eight years earlier, he had worked for renowned jazz trumpeter Cootie Williams as his road manager.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Cootie Williams bought a home in Addisleigh Park in 1947.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] While residing in Addisleigh Park, Mercer Ellington employed Dizzy Gillespie, Kenny Dorham, and Charles Mingus.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Throughout the 1940s, Mercer and his father, Duke Ellington, frequently borrowed musicians from one another's ensembles.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Saxophonist Earl Bostic moved to Addisleigh Park in 1948, the same year Bostic's sextet hit success with their first single "Temptation".
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] In the early 1930s, he played with Midwestern territory bands before moving to New York City in 1938 to play with Don Redman.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Bostic's second hit, "Flamingo", was produced in 1951, while he was still living in Addisleigh Park.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] In 1956, Bostic and his wife left Addisleigh Park to settle in Los Angeles.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Earl Bostic died onstage from a heart attack in Rochester, New York, in 1965.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Bostic's neighbors on Murdock Avenue were Ella Fitzgerald and her then-husband, famous bassist and cellist Ray Brown.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Fitzgerald owned her Addisleigh Park home from 1949 until 1956.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] During the late 1930s and early 1940s, Fitzgerald had become one of the most recognizable names of wide-release swing music in the United States.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] She met Brown in 1946 while on tour with Dizzy Gillespie's band.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Between the years 1949 and 1956, Fitzgerald sang scat with various bebop bands.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] She was awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom by President George H.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Vicksburg, Mississippi, native and famous jazz bassist Milt Hinton moved into Addisleigh Park in 1950.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] In his younger years, he had lived and worked in Chicago alongside celebrated jazz musicians Art Tatum and Eddie South.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] He moved to New York City for a job in Cab Calloway's orchestra in 1936.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Hinton bought a home on 113th Avenue in Addisleigh Park in 1950.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] He lived in the neighborhood until his death in 2000.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Saxophonist John Coltrane bought a home on Mexico Street in Addisleigh Park in the year 1959.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] Coltrane had just met tremendous critical success after his collaborations with Thelonious Monk and Miles Davis.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] In January 1960, Coltrane released *Giant Steps*, his first album with Atlantic Records.
[src:laurelton-queens/addisleigh-park] *Giant Steps* is considered to be the album that catapulted Coltrane into jazz legend.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Census Bureau and the Office of Management and Budget (OMB) define a set of self-identified categories of race and ethnicity chosen by residents, with which they most closely identify.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Residents can indicate their origins alongside their race, and are asked specifically whether they are of Hispanic or Latino origin in a separate question.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Race and ethnicity are considered separate and distinct identities, with a person's origins considered in the census.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Racial categories in the United States represent a social-political construct for the race or races that respondents consider themselves to be and, "generally reflect a social definition of race recognized in this country".
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] From the first United States Census in 1790 to the 1960 Census, the government's census enumerators chose a person's race.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Racial categories changed over time, with different groups being added and removed with each census.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Since the 1970 Census, Americans provide their own racial self-identification.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] This change was due to the reforms brought about by the Civil Rights Act of 1964 and the Voting Rights Act of 1965, which required more accurate census data.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Since the 2000 Census, Americans have been able to identify as more than one race.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] In 1997, the OMB issued a Federal Register notice regarding revisions to the standards for the classification of federal data on race and ethnicity.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The OMB developed race and ethnic standards in order to provide "consistent data on race and ethnicity throughout the federal government".
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The development of the data standards stem in large measure from new responsibilities to enforce civil rights laws.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Prior to this decision, the census and other government data collections asked people to report singular races.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] As of 2023, the OMB built on the 1997 guidelines and suggested the addition of a Middle Eastern or North African (MENA) racial category and considered combining racial and ethnic categories into one question.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] In March 2024, the Office of Management and Budget published revisions to Statistical Policy Directive No.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] 15: Standards for Maintaining, Collecting, and Presenting Federal Data on Race and Ethnicity that included a combined question and a MENA category, while also collecting additional detail to enable data disaggregation.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The OMB states, "many federal programs are put into effect based on the race data obtained from the decennial census (i.e., promoting equal employment opportunities; assessing racial disparities in health and environmental risks).
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Race data is also critical for the basic research behind many policy decisions.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] States require this data to meet legislative redistricting requirements.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The data is needed to monitor compliance with the Voting Rights Act by local jurisdictions".
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Data on ethnic groups are important for putting into effect a number of federal statutes (i.e., enforcing bilingual election rules under the Voting Rights Act and monitoring/enforcing equal employment opportunities under the Civil Rights Act).
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The 1790 United States census was the first census in the history of the United States.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The population of the United States was recorded as 3,929,214 as of Census Day, August 2, 1790, as mandated by Article I, Section 2 of the US Constitution and applicable laws.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The US Marshals were also responsible for governing the census.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] About one-third of the original census data has been lost or destroyed since documentation.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The data was lost in 1790–1830, and included data from Connecticut, Delaware, Georgia, Maine, Maryland, Massachusetts, New Hampshire, New Jersey, New York, North Carolina, Pennsylvania, Rhode Island, South Carolina, Vermont, and Virginia.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] However, the census was proven factual and the existence of most of this data can be confirmed in many secondary sources pertaining to the first census.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Thomas Jefferson, then the Secretary of State, directed US Marshals to collect data from all 13 original states, and from the Southwest Territory.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The census was not conducted in Vermont until 1791, after that state's admission to the Union as the 14th state on March 4 of that year.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The figures for Massachusetts do not include the population of Maine.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Though Maine was then a part of Massachusetts, the Maine figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Maine.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Corrected figures are 59,096, or 2 more than figures published in 1790, due to error in addition.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The figures for Virginia do not include the population of Kentucky.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Though Kentucky was then a part of Virginia, the Kentucky figures were compiled separately, and are shown on the line for Kentucky.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The Virginia figures do include the portion of Virginia that later became the state of West Virginia.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Some doubt surrounded the numbers, as President George Washington and Thomas Jefferson maintained the population was undercounted.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The potential reasons Washington and Jefferson may have thought this could be refusal to participate, poor public transportation and roads, spread-out population, and restraints of current technology.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] No microdata from the 1790 population census are available, but aggregate data for small areas and their compatible cartographic boundary files, can be downloaded from the National Historical Geographic Information System.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] However, the categories of "Free white males" of 16 years and upward, including heads of families under 16 years, "Free white females", including heads of families, All other free persons, and "Slaves," existed in the census form.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] In 1800 and 1810, the age question regarding free white males was more detailed with five cohorts and included All other free persons, except "Indians not taxed", and "Slaves".
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The 1820 census built on the questions asked in 1810 by asking age questions about slaves.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Also the term "colored" entered the census nomenclature.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] In addition, a question stating "Number of foreigners not naturalized" was included.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] In the 1830 census, a new question, which stated, "The number of White persons who were foreigners not naturalized" was included.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The 1840 census was the last census conducted by U.S. marshals.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] This was due to the Northern members of the Whig Party opposing the controversial claim in the 1840 census that free Black Americans in the Northern United States suffered from a higher degree of "insane" or "idiotic" behavior compared to enslaved Black Americans.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Starting in 1850, the Department of the Interior used a specialized census bureau to tabulate the census.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The 1850 census had a dramatic shift in the way information about residents was collected.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] For the first time, free persons were listed individually instead of by head of household.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Two questionnaires were used – one for free inhabitants and one for slaves.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The question on the free inhabitants schedule about color was a column that was to be left blank if a person were white, marked "B" if a person were black, and marked "M" if a person were mulatto.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Slaves were listed by owner, and classified by gender and age, not individually, and the question about color was a column that was to be marked with a "B" if the slave were black and an "M" if mulatto.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] For 1890, the Census Office changed the design of the population questionnaire.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Residents were still listed individually, but a new questionnaire sheet was used for each family.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Additionally, this was the first year that the census distinguished among different Asian ethnic groups, such as Japanese and Chinese, due to increased immigration.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] This census also marked the beginning of the term "race" in the questionnaires.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Enumerators were instructed to write "White", "Black", "Mulatto", "Quadroon", "Octoroon", "Chinese", "Japanese", or "Indian".
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] During 1900, the "Color or Race" question was slightly modified, removing the term "Mulatto".
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The 1910 census was similar to that of 1900, but it included a reinsertion of "Mulatto" and a question about the "mother tongue" of foreign-born individuals and individuals with foreign-born parents.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] "Ot" was also added to signify "other races", with space for a race to be written in.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] This decade's version of the Indian Population Schedule featured questions asking the individual's proportion of white, black, or American Indian lineage.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The 1920 census questionnaire was similar to 1910, but excluded a separate schedule for American Indians.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] "Hin", "Kor", and "Fil" were also added to the "Color or Race" question, signifying Hindu (Asian Indian), Korean, and Filipino, respectively.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The biggest change in this census was in racial classification.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Enumerators were instructed to no longer use the "Mulatto" classification.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Instead, they were given special instructions for reporting the race of interracial persons.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] A person with both white and black ancestry (termed "blood") was to be recorded as "Negro", no matter the fraction of that lineage (the "one-drop rule").
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] A person of mixed black and American Indian ancestry was also to be recorded as "Neg" (for "Negro") unless they were considered to be "predominantly" American Indian and accepted as such within the community.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] A person with both white and American Indian ancestry was to be recorded as American Indian, unless their Indigenous ancestry was small, and they were accepted as white within the community.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] In all situations in which a person had white and some other racial ancestry, they were to be reported as that other race.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] People who had minority interracial ancestry were to be reported as the race of their father.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] For the first and only time, "Mexican" was listed as a race.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Enumerators were instructed that all people born in Mexico, or whose parents were born in Mexico, should be listed as Mexicans, and not under any other racial category.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] In prior censuses and in 1940, enumerators were instructed to list Mexican Americans as white, perhaps because some of them were of white background (mainly Spanish), many others mixed white and Native American and some of them Native American.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The supplemental American Indian questionnaire was back, but in abbreviated form.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] It featured a question asking if the person was of full or mixed American Indian ancestry.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Roosevelt promoted a Good Neighbor policy that sought better relations with Mexico.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] In 1935, a federal judge ruled that three Mexican immigrants were ineligible for citizenship because they were not white, as required by federal law.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Mexico protested, and Roosevelt decided to circumvent the decision and make sure the federal government treated Hispanics as white.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The State Department, the Census Bureau, the Labor Department, and other government agencies therefore made sure to uniformly classify people of Mexican descent as white.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] This policy encouraged the League of United Latin American Citizens in its quest to minimize discrimination by asserting their whiteness.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The 1940 census was the first to include separate population and housing questionnaires.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The race category of "Mexican" was eliminated in 1940, and the population of Mexican descent was counted with the white population.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] 1940 census data was used for Japanese American internment.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The Census Bureau's role was denied for decades, but was finally proven in 2007.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The 1950 census questionnaire removed the word "color" from the racial question, and also removed Hindu and Korean from the race choices.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The 1960 census re-added the word "color" to the racial question, and changed "Indian" to "American Indian", as well as adding Hawaiian, Part-Hawaiian, Aleut, and Eskimo.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The "Other (print out race)" option was removed.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] This year's census included "Negro or Black", re-added Korean and the Other race option.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] East Indians (the term used at that time for people whose ancestry is from the Indian subcontinent) were counted as White.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] There was a questionnaire that was asked of only a sample of respondents.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] This year added several options to the race question, including Vietnamese, Indian (East), Guamanian, Samoan, and re-added Aleut.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Is this person of Spanish/Hispanic origin or descent?
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The racial categories in this year are as they appear in the 2000 and 2010 censuses.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The 1990 census was not designed to capture multiple racial responses, and when individuals marked the "other" race option and provided a multiple write-in.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The response was assigned according to the race written first.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Is this person of Spanish/Hispanic origin?
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Yes, other Spanish/Hispanic, print one group ...
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Race was asked differently in the 2000 census in several other ways than previously.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Most significantly, respondents were given the option of selecting one or more race categories to indicate racial identities.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Data show that nearly seven million Americans identified as members of two or more races.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Because of these changes, the 2000 census data on race are not directly comparable with data from the 1990 census or earlier censuses.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Use of caution is therefore recommended when interpreting changes in the racial composition of the US population over time.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The following definitions apply to the 2000 census only.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The federal government of the United States has mandated that "in data collection and presentation, federal agencies are required to use a minimum of two ethnicities: "Hispanic or Latino" and "Not Hispanic or Latino".
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Use of the word "ethnicity" for Hispanics only is considerably more restricted than its conventional meaning, which covers other distinctions, some of which are covered by the "race" and "ancestry" questions.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The distinct questions accommodate the possibility of Hispanic and Latino Americans' also declaring various racial identities (see also White Hispanic and Latino Americans, Black Hispanic and Latino Americans, and Asian Hispanic and Latino Americans).
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] In the 2000 census, 12.5% of the US population reported "Hispanic or Latino" ethnicity and 87.5% reported "Not-Hispanic or Latino" ethnicity.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The 2010 census included changes designed to more clearly distinguish Hispanic ethnicity as not being a race.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] That included adding the sentence: "For this census, Hispanic origins are not races." Additionally, the Hispanic terms were modified from "Hispanic or Latino" to "Hispanic, Latino or Spanish origin".
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Although used in the census and the American Community Survey, "Some other race" is not an official race, and the Bureau considered eliminating it prior to the 2000 census.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The Interagency Committee has suggested that the concept of marking multiple boxes be extended to the Hispanic origin question, thereby freeing individuals from having to choose between their parents' ethnic heritages.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] In other words, a respondent could choose both "Hispanic or Latino" and "Not Hispanic or Latino".
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The 2020 census featured similar designs to the 2000 and 2010 censuses.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Subsequently, the Census Bureau adhered to the 1997 OMB standards and thus used two separate questions to collect data on race and ethnicity.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] However, there were improvements in the phrasing of the race and ethnicity questions within the OMB guidelines, that would enhance clarity for respondents.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The Hispanic origin question included the same checkboxes as the 2010 census ("Mexican, Mexican Am., Chicano", "Puerto Rican", "Cuban"), along with a "Yes, another Hispanic, Latino, or Spanish origin".
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Under this category, two changes emerged.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The first was the shift from "Print origin, for example" to "Print, for example".
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The removal of the word origin was due to the surveyed confusion and differentiating meanings origin has for respondents or varying backgrounds.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Furthermore, the Census Bureau updated the write-in instructions for the "Some Other Race" category and included the instruction to "Print race", but changed the instruction to read "Print race or origin" to match the primary instruction to "*Mark ☒ one or more boxes **AND** print origins*".
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] According to the United States Census Bureau, as a result of significant feedback, a detailed write-in response and example were included for the "White" and the "Black or African Am." racial categories to compensate a wider horizon of identities.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] There were also six example groups for each of the "White", "Black or African American", and "American Indian or Alaska Native" racial categories.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] In addition, after 100 years, the term "Negro" was removed from the 2020 census, as a large portion of respondents advocated for its removal.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Instead, the category shifted from "Black, African Am., or Negro" to "Black or African Am." on paper questionnaires and electronic instruments.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The identification of the term African American first occurred in the 2000 census, reflecting a long-standing history of offensive terminology since the censuses' inception.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The 1790 census included other "free persons" by color and "slaves".
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] From 1850 to 1880, the codes for enumerators were generally Black (B) and Mulatto (M).
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] In 1900, there were no specified categories on the census listing form, and the instructions called for enumerators to list "B" for "Black (or negro or negro descent)", displaying the first occurrence of the controversial term "Negro".
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] In 1930, there were specific instructions that used the term "Negro".
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Mixed persons were to be counted as "Negro" no matter how small the share of blood, also known as the one-drop rule.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] It was not until 1970 that the term Black appeared on a census form, and in 1990 the enumerator of color was eliminated.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The 2020 census was also "the first to specifically solicit Middle Eastern North African (MENA) responses" through the write-in response for the White racial category.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The term MENA includes the Arab American population, which is growing quickly as of 2023.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] This allowed the 2020 census to include dis-aggregated data on MENA populations, which made up over 3.5 million Americans.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] California, New York, and Michigan have the largest MENA populations, and Lebanese, Iranian, and Egyptian populations made up nearly half of them.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] This was almost triple the 2000 census' estimate of a population of 1.2 million Arab Americans, based on the "Ancestry" question rather than the racial category question.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] That number may have been an under count however, as 19% of the American population provided no answer for the "Ancestry" question.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] This is significant because MENA identities were previously only tracked through the "Ancestry" write-in question on the American Community Survey in 2010.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The Arab American population was then estimated through the number of responses that included one or more Arab ancestries.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The 2020 census changed this by explicitly prompting write-in responses with Arab American examples listed as "Print, for example, German, Irish, English, Italian, Lebanese, Egyptian, etc".
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The improvements are part of a larger effort reviewing the 1997 OMB guidelines, specifically to move MENA from under the White racial category into a new label.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] An OMB working group officially recommended a new MENA category in 2023 based on public feedback going back to 2015 and "plans to make final decisions on revisions by Summer 2024".
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Many people in the community "may not be perceived, nor perceive themselves, to be White".
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The added category could allow for more targeted funding, social programs, and political representation.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] A follow-up survey concluded that the miscounting of children under five years of age and that American Indians and Alaska Natives living on reservations continued to have the highest net undercount rate, similar to 2010.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] One of the leading factors of the misrepresented information in the 2020 census is the coronavirus pandemic, which caused notable delays in the Census Bureau's Post-Enumeration Survey.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The Post-Enumeration Survey is used to determine how accurate the census results are and inform planning for the next national count in 2030.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Furthermore, discrepancies persisted due to the irrefutable variables of delays to field work, migration of many college students and others, and some respondents failed to answer the necessary questions required for the Post-Enumeration Survey to match the census.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Translating the data set, the 3.45 difference in net coverage error for the Hispanic or Latino category proves widely problematic, but is an avid reflection of the seismic shifts in the United States.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Mexican immigrants have been at the center of one of the largest mass migrations in contemporary history, reaching a peak of 12.8 million in 2007, but have since declined, as reported by the Pew Research Center.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The predominant reasoning being shifts in political authority and the coronavirus pandemic resulting in policy changes.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] More specifically, immigrants entering through a permanent legal residency (green card), visa overstays, and apprehensions have drastically changed the input and output of data.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The total number of non-immigrant visas processed in Mexico by the US Department of State dropped 35% in 2020 compared with the prior year, from about 1.5 million in 2019 to about 960,000 in 2020.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The temporary visas were processed for tourism, business, or crossing the border.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Consequently, due to political shifts, apprehensions of unauthorized Mexican immigrants increased considerably after the pandemic started in 2020.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] From October 1, 2019 to September 30, 2020, the number of detainments of Mexican adults at the US-Mexican border reached its highest levels since 2013 under president Donald Trump.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] There were 253,118 such encounters, up 52% from 166,458 the previous year.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The Census Bureau warns that data on race in 2000 census are not directly comparable to those collected in previous censuses.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Many residents of the United States consider race and ethnicity to be the same.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] In the 2000 census, respondents were tallied in each of the race groups they reported.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] Consequently, the total of each racial category exceeds the total population because some people reported more than one race.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The Census Bureau implemented a Census Quality Survey, gathering data from about 50,000 households to assess the reporting of race and Hispanic origin in the 2000 census with the purpose of creating a way to make comparisons between the 2000 census with previous census racial data.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] In September 1997, during the process of revision of racial categories previously declared by OMB Directive No.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] 15, the American Anthropological Association (AAA) recommended that OMB combine the "race" and "ethnicity" categories into one question to appear as "race/ethnicity" for the 2000 census.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] The recommendations of the AAA were not adopted by the Census Bureau for the 2000, 2010, and 2020 censuses.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] This includes Hispanic, Latino, or Spanish origin, which remained an ethnicity, not a race.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] While race/ethnicity definitions for 2020 remained consistent, individuals who identify as White, Black/African American, and/or American Indian or Alaska Native were asked to specifically identify their racial origins.
[src:laurelton-queens/african-american-u-s-census] In 2001, the National Institutes of Health adopted the new language to comply with the revisions to Directive 15, as did the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission of the United States Department of Labor in 2007.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] During the colonial era, Sephardic Jews who arrived via Portugal and via Brazil (Dutch Brazil) represented the bulk of America's then small Jewish population.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The American Jewish community manifests a wide range of Jewish cultural traditions, encompassing the full spectrum of Jewish religious observance.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Depending on religious definitions and varying population data, the United States has the largest or second largest Jewish community in the world, after Israel.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] As of 2020, the American Jewish population is estimated at 7.5 million people, accounting for 2.4% of the total US population.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] This includes 4.2 million adults who identify their religion as Jewish, 1.5 million Jewish adults who identify with no religion, and 1.8 million Jewish children.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] It is estimated that up to 15 million Americans are part of the "enlarged" American Jewish population, accounting for 4.5% of the total US population, consisting of those who have at least one Jewish grandparent and would be eligible for Israeli citizenship under the Law of Return.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Jews were present in the Thirteen Colonies since the mid-17th century.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] However, they were few in number, with at most 200 to 300 having arrived by 1700.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Those early arrivals were mostly Sephardi Jewish immigrants, of Western Sephardic (also known as Spanish and Portuguese Jewish) ancestry, but by 1720, Ashkenazi Jews from diaspora communities in Central and Eastern Europe predominated.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] For the first time, the English Plantation Act 1740 permitted Jews to become British citizens and emigrate to the colonies.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The first famous Jew in US history was Chaim Salomon, a Polish-born Jew who emigrated to New York and played an important role in the American Revolution.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] He was a successful financier who supported the patriotic cause and helped raise most of the money needed to finance the American Revolution.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Despite some of them being denied the right to vote or hold office in local jurisdictions, Sephardi Jews became active in community affairs in the 1790s, after they were granted political equality in the five states where they were most numerous.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Until about 1830, Charleston, South Carolina had more Jews than anywhere else in North America.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Large-scale Jewish immigration commenced in the 19th century, when, by mid-century, many German Jews had arrived, migrating to the United States in large numbers due to antisemitic laws and restrictions in their countries of birth.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] They primarily became merchants and shop-owners.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Gradually early Jewish arrivals from the east coast would travel westward, and in the fall of 1819 the first Jewish religious services west of the Appalachian Range were conducted during the High Holidays in Cincinnati, the oldest Jewish community in the Midwest.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Gradually the Cincinnati Jewish community would adopt novel practices under the leadership Rabbi Isaac Meyer Wise, the father of Reform Judaism in the United States, such as the inclusion of women in *minyan*.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] By 1880 there were approximately 250,000 Jews in the United States, many of them being the educated, and largely secular, German Jews, although a minority population of the older Sephardi Jewish families remained influential.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Jewish migration to the United States increased dramatically in the early 1880s, as a result of persecution and economic difficulties in parts of Eastern Europe.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Most of these new immigrants were Yiddish-speaking Ashkenazi Jews, most of whom arrived from poor diaspora communities of the Russian Empire and the Pale of Settlement, located in modern-day Poland, Lithuania, Belarus, Ukraine, and Moldova.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] During the same period, great numbers of Ashkenazic Jews also arrived from Galicia, at that time the most impoverished region of the Austro-Hungarian Empire with a heavy Jewish urban population, driven out mainly by economic reasons.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Over 2,000,000 Jews landed between the late 19th century and 1924 when the Immigration Act of 1924 restricted immigration.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Most settled in the New York metropolitan area, establishing the world's major concentrations of the Jewish population.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] In 1915, the circulation of the daily Yiddish newspapers was half a million in New York City alone, and 600,000 nationally.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] In addition, thousands more subscribed to the numerous weekly papers and the many magazines in Yiddish.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] At the beginning of the 1900s, these newly arrived Jews built support networks consisting of many small synagogues and *Landsmanshaften* (German and Yiddish for "Countryman Associations") for Jews from the same town or village.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] American Jewish writers of the time urged assimilation and integration into the wider American culture, and Jews quickly became part of American life.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Approximately 500,000 American Jews (or half of all Jewish males between 18 and 50) fought in World War II, and after the war younger families joined the new trend of suburbanization.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] There, Jews became increasingly assimilated and demonstrated rising intermarriage.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The suburbs facilitated the formation of new centers, as Jewish school enrollment more than doubled between the end of World War II and the mid-1950s, while synagogue affiliation jumped from 20% in 1930 to 60% in 1960; the fastest growth came in Reform and, especially, Conservative congregations.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] More recent waves of Jewish emigration from Russia and other regions have largely joined the mainstream American Jewish community.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Americans of Jewish descent have been successful in many fields and aspects over the years.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The Jewish community in America has gone from being part of the lower class of society, with numerous employments barred to them, to being a group with a high concentrations in members of the academia and a per capita income higher than the average in the United States.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Scholars debate whether the historical experience of Jews in the United States has been such a unique experience as to validate American exceptionalism.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Korelitz (1996) shows how American Jews during the late 19th and early 20th centuries abandoned a racial definition of Jewishness in favor of one that embraced ethnicity.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The key to understanding this transition from a racial self-definition to a cultural or ethnic one can be found in the *Menorah Journal* between 1915 and 1925.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] During this time contributors to the Menorah promoted a cultural, rather than a racial, religious, or other views of Jewishness as a means to define Jews in a world that threatened to overwhelm and absorb Jewish uniqueness.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The journal represented the ideals of the menorah movement established by Horace M.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Kallen and others to promote a revival in Jewish cultural identity and combat the idea of race as a means to define or identify peoples.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Siporin (1990) states that the family folklore of ethnic Jews provides insights that illuminate collective history and transform it into art, and that these insights tell us how Jews have survived being uprooted and transformed.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Many immigrant narratives bear a theme of the arbitrary nature of fate and the reduced state of immigrants in a new culture.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] By contrast, ethnic family narratives tend to show the ethnicity more in charge of his life, and perhaps in danger of losing his Jewishness altogether.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Some stories show how a family member successfully negotiated the conflict between ethnic and American identities.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] After 1960, memories of the Holocaust, together with the Six-Day War in 1967 had major impacts on fashioning Jewish ethnic identity.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Some have argued that the Holocaust highlighted for Jews the importance of their ethnic identity at a time when other minorities were asserting their own.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The world's largest Jewish gathering outside of Israel occurred in Edison, central New Jersey, on December 1, 2024.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] During the World War II period, the American Jewish community was bitterly and deeply divided and as a result, it was unable to form a united front.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Most Jews who had previously emigrated to the United States from Eastern Europe supported Zionism, because they believed that a return to their ancestral homeland was the only solution to the persecution and the genocide which were then occurring across Europe.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] One important development was the sudden conversion of many American Jewish leaders to Zionism late in the war.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The Holocaust was largely ignored by American media as it was happening.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Reporters and editors largely did not believe the stories of atrocities which were coming out of Europe.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The Holocaust had a profound impact on the Jewish community in the United States, especially after 1960 as Holocaust education improved, as Jews tried to comprehend what had happened during it, and especially as they tried to commemorate it and grapple with it when they looked to the future.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Abraham Joshua Heschel summarized this dilemma when he attempted to understand Auschwitz: "To try to answer is to commit a supreme blasphemy.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Members of the American Jewish community have included prominent participants in civil rights movements.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] In the mid-20th century, there were American Jews who were among the most active participants in the Civil Rights Movement and feminist movements.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] A number of American Jews have also been active figures in the struggle for gay rights in America.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] From our Jewish historic experience of three and a half thousand years we say: Our ancient history began with slavery and the yearning for freedom.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] During the Middle Ages my people lived for a thousand years in the ghettos of Europe. ...
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] It is for these reasons that it is not merely sympathy and compassion for the black people of America that motivates us.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] As of 2020, the American Jewish population is, depending on the method of identification, either the largest in the world, or the second-largest in the world (after Israel).
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Precise population figures vary depending on whether Jews are accounted for based on halakhic considerations, or secular, political and ancestral identification factors.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] There were about four million adherents of Judaism in the US as of 2001, approximately 1.4% of the US population.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] According to the Jewish Agency, for the year 2023 Israel was home to 7.2 million Jews (46% of the world's Jewish population), while the United States contained 6.3 million (40.1%).
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] According to Gallup and Pew Research Center findings, "at maximum 2.2% of the US adult population has some basis for Jewish self-identification." In 2020, the demographers Arnold Dashefsky and Ira M.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Sheskin estimated in the American Jewish Yearbook that the American Jewish population totaled 7.15 million, making up 2.17% of the country's 329.5 million inhabitants.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] In the same year, the American Jewish population was estimated at 7.6 million people, accounting for 2.4% of the total US population, by other organization.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] This includes 4.9 million adults who identify their religion as Jewish, 1.2 million Jewish adults who identify with no religion, and 1.6 million Jewish children.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] According to a 2020 study by the Pew Research Center, the core American Jewish population is estimated at 7.5 million people, this includes 5.8 million Jewish adults.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The study found that the median age of the American Jewish population is 49, and around 18% of American Jewish are under the age of 30, while 49% of American Jewish are ages 50 and older.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The study found also that 9% of American Jewish identify as LGBT.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The *American Jewish Yearbook population survey* had placed the number of American Jews at 6.4 million, or approximately 2.1% of the total population.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] This figure is significantly higher than the previous large scale survey estimate, conducted by the 2000–2001 National Jewish Population estimates, which estimated 5.2 million Jews.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] A 2007 study released by the Steinhardt Social Research Institute (SSRI) at Brandeis University presents evidence to suggest that both these figures may be underestimations with a potential 7.0–7.4 million Americans of Jewish descent.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Those higher estimates were however arrived at by including all non-Jewish family members and household members, rather than surveyed individuals.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] In a 2019 study by Jews of Color Initiative it was found that approximately 12-15% of Jews in the United States, about 1,000,000 of 7,200,000 identify as multiracial and Jews of color.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The overall population of Americans of Jewish descent is demographically characterized by an aging population composition and low fertility rates significantly below generational replacement.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] However, the Orthodox Jewish population, concentrated in the Northeastern United States, has fertility rates when taken alone which are significantly higher than both generational replacement and that of the average U.S. population.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The National Jewish Population Survey of 1990 asked 4.5 million adult Jews to identify their denomination.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Pew's 2020 poll found that 37% affiliated with Reform Judaism, 17% with Conservative Judaism, and 9% with Orthodox Judaism.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Young Jews are more likely to identify as Orthodox or as unaffiliated compared to older members of the Jewish community.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Many Jews are concentrated in the Northeastern United States, particularly around New York City.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The world's largest menorah is lit annually at Grand Army Plaza in Manhattan, while the largest menorah in New Jersey is similarly celebrated in Monroe Township, Middlesex County.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Many Jews also live in South Florida, Los Angeles, and other large metropolitan areas, like Chicago, San Francisco, or Atlanta.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The metropolitan areas of New York City, Los Angeles, and Miami contain nearly one quarter of the world's Jews and the New York City metropolitan area itself contains around a quarter of all Jews living in the United States.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] According to a 2025 study of Jewish Life in North America, some 22% of US Jews live in small communities, defined as Jewish communities with fewer than 5,000 Jews living within five miles of their ZIP code.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] According to a study published by demographers and sociologists Ira M.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The New York City metropolitan area is the second-largest Jewish population center in the world after the Tel Aviv metropolitan area in Israel.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Several other major cities have large Jewish communities, including Los Angeles, Miami, Baltimore, Boston, Chicago, San Francisco and Philadelphia.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] In many metropolitan areas, the majority of Jewish families live in suburban areas.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The Greater Phoenix area was home to about 83,000 Jews in 2002, and has been rapidly growing.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The phenomenon of Israeli migration to the US is often termed *Yerida*.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The Israeli immigrant community in America is less widespread.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The significant Israeli immigrant communities in the United States are in the New York City metropolitan area, Los Angeles, Miami, and Chicago.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] According to the 2001 undertaking of the National Jewish Population Survey, 4.3 million American Jews have some sort of strong connection to the Jewish community, whether religious or cultural.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] These parallel themes have facilitated the extraordinary economic, political, and social success of the American Jewish community, but also have contributed to widespread cultural assimilation.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] More recently however, the propriety and degree of assimilation has also become a significant and controversial issue within the modern American Jewish community, with both political and religious skeptics.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] While not all Jews disapprove of intermarriage, many members of the Jewish community have become concerned that the high rate of interfaith marriage will result in the eventual disappearance of the American Jewish community.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Intermarriage rates have risen from roughly 6% in 1950 and 25% in 1974, to approximately 40–50% in the year 2000.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] By 2013, the intermarriage rate had risen to 71% for non-Orthodox Jews.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] This, in combination with the comparatively low birthrate in the Jewish community, has led to a 5% decline in the Jewish population of the United States in the 1990s.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] In addition to this, when compared with the general American population, the American Jewish community is slightly older.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] A third of intermarried couples provide their children with a Jewish upbringing, and doing so is more common among intermarried families raising their children in areas with high Jewish populations.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The Boston area, for example, is exceptional in that an estimated 60% of children of intermarriages are being raised Jewish, meaning that intermarriage would actually be contributing to a net *increase* in the number of Jews.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] As well, some children raised through intermarriage rediscover and embrace their Jewish roots when they themselves marry and have children.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] In contrast to the ongoing trends of assimilation, some communities within American Jewry, such as Orthodox Jews, have significantly higher birth rates and lower intermarriage rates, and are growing rapidly.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The proportion of Jewish synagogue members who were Orthodox rose from 11% in 1971 to 21% in 2000, while the overall Jewish community declined in number.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Data from the Pew Center shows that, as of 2013, 27% of American Jews under the age of 18 live in Orthodox households, a dramatic increase from Jews aged 18 to 29, only 11% of whom are Orthodox.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The UJA-Federation of New York reports that 60% of Jewish children in the New York City area live in Orthodox homes.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] In addition to economizing and sharing, many Haredi communities depend on government aid to support their high birth rate and large families.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The Hasidic village of New Square, New York receives Section 8 housing subsidies at a higher rate than the rest of the region, and half of the population in the Hasidic village of Kiryas Joel, New York receive food stamps, while a third receive Medicaid.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] About half of the American Jews are considered to be religious.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Out of this 2,831,000 religious Jewish population, 92% are non-Hispanic white, 5% Hispanic (Most commonly from Argentina, Venezuela, or Cuba), 1% Asian, 1% black and 1% Other (mixed-race etc.).
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Almost this many non-religious Jews exist in the United States.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The United States Census Bureau classifies most American Jews as white.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Jewish people are culturally diverse and may be of any race, ethnicity, or national origin.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Many American Jews identify themselves as being both Jewish and white, while many solely identify as Jewish, resisting this identification.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Several commentators have observed that "many American Jews retain a feeling of ambivalence about whiteness".
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Karen Brodkin explains this ambivalence as rooted in anxieties about the potential loss of Jewish identity, especially outside of intellectual elites.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Similarly, Kenneth Marcus observes a number of ambivalent cultural phenomena which have also been noted by other scholars, and he concludes that "the veneer of whiteness has not established conclusively the racial construction of American Jews".
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The relationship between Jewish identity and white majority identity continues to be described as "complicated" for many American Jews, particularly Ashkenazi and Sephardi Jews of European descent.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The issue of Jewish whiteness may be different for many Mizrahi, Sephardi, Black, Asian, and Latino Jews, many of whom may never be considered white by society.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Many American white nationalists and white supremacists view all Jews as non-white, even if they are of European descent.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Some white nationalists believe that Jews can be white and a small number of white nationalists are Jewish.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] According to the Pew Research Center, fewer than 1% of American Jews in 2020 identified as Asian Americans.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Around 1% of religious Jews identified as Asian American.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] A small but growing community of around 350 Indian American Jews lives in the New York City metropolitan area, in both New York state and New Jersey.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Many are members of India's Bene Israel community.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The Indian Jewish Congregation of USA, headquartered in New York City, is the center of the organized community.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Jews of European descent are classified as white by the US census and have generally been classified as legally white throughout American history as pertaining to courts, naturalization law, and censuses.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] However, Jews long struggled with social equality and had an ambivalent relationship to being part of a white majority in America.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Many American Jews of European descent identify themselves as being both Jewish and white, while others solely identify themselves as being Jewish or identify as both Jewish and non-white.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] However, Jews of European descent rarely identify as Jews of color.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] According to the Pew Research Center, the majority of American Jews are non-Hispanic white Ashkenazi Jews.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The relationship between American Jews and white majority identity continues to be described as "complicated".
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Many American white nationalists view Jews as non-white.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Jews of Middle Eastern and North African descent (often referred to as Mizrahi Jews) are classified as white by the US census.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Mizrahi Jews sometimes identify as Jews of color, but often do not, and they may or may not be considered people of color by society.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Syrian Jews rarely identify as Jews of color.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Many Syrian Jews identify as white, Middle Eastern, or otherwise non-white rather than as Jews of color.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Estimates of the number of American Jews of African descent in the United States range from 20,000 to 200,000.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Jews of African descent belong to all American Jewish denominations.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Like their other Jewish counterparts, some black Jews are atheists.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Notable African American Jews include Drake, Lenny Kravitz, Lisa Bonet, Sammy Davis Jr., Rashida Jones, Ros Gold-Onwude, Yaphet Kotto, Jordan Farmar, Taylor Mays, Daveed Diggs, Alicia Garza, Tiffany Haddish, and rabbis Capers Funnye and Alysa Stanton.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Hispanic Jews have lived in what is now the United States since colonial times.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The earliest Hispanic Jewish settlers were Sephardi Jews from Spain and Portugal.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Beginning in the 1500s, some of the Spanish settlers in what is now New Mexico and Texas were Crypto-Jews, but there was no organized Jewish presence.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Later waves of Sephardi immigration brought Judeo-Spanish speaking Jews from the Ottoman Empire, in what is now Greece, Turkey, Bulgaria, Libya, and Syria.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] These Spanish-speaking Sephardi Jews, as well as Sephardi Jews of European descent, such as the Spanish and Portuguese Jews, are sometimes considered culturally but not ethnically Hispanic.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Hispanic and Latin American Jews, particularly Hispanic and Latin American Ashkenazi Jews, often identify as white rather than as Jews of color.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Some Jews with roots in Latin America may not identify as "Hispanic" or "Latino" at all, usually due to their recent European immigrant origins.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] American Jews of Argentine, Brazilian, and Mexican descent are often Ashkenazi, but some are Sephardi.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] A majority of the Jewish population in the United States are Ashkenazi Jews who descend from diaspora Jewish populations of Central and Eastern Europe.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Most American Ashkenazi Jews are non-Hispanic whites, but a minority are Jews of color, Hispanic/Latino, or both.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Largely expelled from the Iberian Peninsula in the late 15th century, Sephardi Jews carried a distinctive Jewish diasporic identity with them to the Americas (although in smaller numbers compared to the Ashkenazi Jewish diaspora) and all other places of their exiled settlement.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] They sometimes settled near existing Jewish communities, such as the one from former Kurdistan, or were the first in new frontiers, with their furthest reach via the Silk Road.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] As a result of the more recent Jewish exodus from Arab lands, many of the Sephardim Tehorim from Western Asia and North Africa relocated to either Israel or France, where they form a significant portion of the Jewish communities today.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Other significant communities of Sephardim Tehorim also migrated in more recent times from the Near East to New York City, Argentina, Costa Rica, Mexico, Montreal, Gibraltar, Puerto Rico, and Dominican Republic.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Because of poverty and turmoil in Latin America, another wave of Sephardic Jews joined other Latin Americans who migrated to the US, Canada, Spain, and other countries of Europe.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Post-1948, Mizrahi Jewish, mostly thousands from Lebanese, Syrian and Egyptian Jewish descent, as well as some from other Middle East and North African Jewish communities migrated to the United States.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Since the 1990s, around 1000 Hebrew-speaking, Ethiopian Jews that had settled in Israel as Ethiopian Jews in Israel re-settled in the United States as Ethiopian Americans, with around half of the Ethiopian Jewish Israeli-American community living in New York.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Education plays a major role as a part of Jewish identity.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] As Jewish culture puts a special premium on it and stresses the importance of cultivation of intellectual pursuits, scholarship, and learning, American Jews as a group tend to be better educated and earn more than Americans as a whole.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Jewish Americans also have an average of 14.7 years of schooling making them the most highly educated of all major religious groups in the United States.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Forty-four percent (55% of Reform Jews) report family incomes of over $100,000 compared to 19% of all Americans, with the next highest group being Hindus at 43%.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] And while 27% of Americans have a four-year university or postgraduate education, 59% (66% of Reform Jews) of American Jews have, the second highest of any ethnic groups after Indian-Americans.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] 75% of American Jews have achieved some form of post-secondary education if two-year vocational and community college diplomas and certificates are also included.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] 31% of American Jews hold a graduate degree; this figure is compared with the general American population where 11% of Americans hold a graduate degree.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] White collar professional jobs have been attractive to Jews and much of the community tend to take up professional white collar careers requiring tertiary education involving formal credentials where the respectability and reputability of professional jobs is highly prized within Jewish culture.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Much of the Jewish American community lead middle class lifestyles.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] While the median household net worth of the typical American family is $99,500, among American Jews the figure is $443,000.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] In addition, the median Jewish American income is estimated to be in the range of $97,000 to $98,000, nearly twice as high the American national median.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Either of these two statistics may be confounded by the fact that the Jewish population is on average older than other religious groups in the country, with 51% of polled adults over the age of 50 compared to 41% nationally.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Older people tend to both have higher income and be more highly educated.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] By 2016, Modern Orthodox Jews had a median household income of $158,000, while Open Orthodox Jews had a median household income at $185,000 (compared to the American median household income of $59,000 for 2016).
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] According to a 2020 study by the Pew Research Center, 23% of American Jewish living in households with incomes of at least $200,000.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Conservatives (27%) and Reforms (26%) are more likely to live in households with incomes of at least $200,000 than those who are Orthodox (16%).
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The study found also that American Jews are a comparatively well-educated group, around 60% of them are college graduates.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Reforms (64%) and Conservatives (55%) are more likely to obtain college or postgraduate education than those who are Orthodox (37%).
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] As a whole, American and Canadian Jews donate more than $9 billion a year to charity.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] This reflects Jewish traditions of supporting social services as a way of living out the dictates of Jewish law.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Most of the charities that benefit are not specifically Jewish organizations.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] While the median income of Jewish Americans is high, some Jewish communities have high levels of poverty.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] In the New York area, there are approximately 560,000 Jews living in poor or near-poor households, representing about 20% of the New York metropolitan Jewish community.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Disability is a major factor in the socioeconomic status of disabled Jews.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Disabled Jews are significantly more likely to be low-income compared to able-bodied Jews, while high-income Jews are significantly less likely to be disabled.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Secular Jews, Jews of no denomination, and people who identify as "just Jewish" are also more likely to live in poverty compared to Jews affiliated with a religious denomination.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] According to analysis by Gallup, American Jews have the highest well-being of any ethnic or religious group in America.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] The great majority of school-age Jewish students attend public schools, although Jewish day schools and yeshivas are to be found throughout the country.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Jewish cultural studies and Hebrew language instruction is also commonly offered at synagogues in the form of supplementary Hebrew schools or Sunday schools.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Jewish enrollment at Cornell's School of Medicine fell from 40% to 4% between the world wars, and Harvard's fell from 30% to 4%.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Before 1945, only a few Jewish professors were permitted as instructors at elite universities.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] In 1941, for example, antisemitism drove Milton Friedman from a non-tenured assistant professorship at the University of Wisconsin–Madison.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Harry Levin became the first Jewish full professor in the Harvard English department in 1943, but the Economics department decided not to hire Paul Samuelson in 1948.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Harvard hired its first Jewish biochemists in 1954.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] According to Clark Kerr, Martin Meyerson in 1965 became the first Jew to serve, albeit temporarily, as the leader of a major American research university.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] That year, Meyerson served as acting chancellor of the University of California, Berkeley, but was unable to obtain a permanent appointment as a result of a combination of tactical errors on his part and antisemitism on the UC Board of Regents.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] Meyerson served as the president of the University of Pennsylvania from 1970 to 1981.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p01] By 1986, a third of the presidents of the elite undergraduate final clubs at Harvard were Jewish.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The American Jews' majority continues to identify themselves with Judaism and its main traditions, such as Conservative, Orthodox and Reform Judaism.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] But, already in the 1980s, 20–30 percent of members of largest Jewish communities, such as of New York City, Chicago, Miami, and others, rejected a denominational label.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] According to the 1990 National Jewish Population Survey, 38% of Jews were affiliated with the Reform tradition, 35% were Conservative, 6% were Orthodox, 1% were Reconstructionists, 10% linked themselves to some other tradition, and 10% said they are "just Jewish".
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Jewish religious practice in America is quite varied.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] According to a 2020 study by the Pew Research Center, 37% of American Jews identify as Reforms, 32% do not with a particular branch, 17% identify as Conservatives, 9% identify as Orthodox, and 4% are members of other Jewish branches, such as Reconstructionist or Humanist Judaism.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The survey found that Jews are far less religious than American adults as a whole, 8% of American Jews go to the synagogue at least once a month, 27% go few times a year, and 56% seldom or never go to the synagogue.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] A 2003 Harris Poll found that 16% of American Jews go to the synagogue at least once a month, 42% go less frequently but at least once a year, and 42% go less frequently than once a year.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The survey found that of the 4.3 million strongly connected Jews, 46% belong to a synagogue.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Among those households who belong to a synagogue, 38% are members of Reform synagogues, 33% Conservative, 22% Orthodox, 2% Reconstructionist, and 5% other types.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Traditionally, Sephardi and Mizrahi Jews do not have different branches (Orthodox, Conservative, Reform, etc.) but usually remain observant and religious.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] However, their synagogues are generally considered Orthodox or Sephardic Haredim by non-Sephardic Jews.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] But, not all Sephardim are Orthodox; among the pioneers of Reform Judaism movement in the 1820s there was the Sephardic congregation Beth Elohim in Charleston, South Carolina.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The survey discovered that Jews in the Northeast and Midwest are generally more observant than Jews in the South or West.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Reflecting a trend also observed among other religious groups, Jews in the Northwestern United States are typically the least observant.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The 2008 American Religious Identification Survey found that around 3.4 million American Jews call themselves religious—out of a general Jewish population of about 5.4 million.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The number of Jews who identify themselves as only culturally Jewish has risen from 20% in 1990 to 37% in 2008, according to the study.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] In the same period, the number of all US adults who said they had no religion rose from 8% to 15%.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Jews are more likely to be secular than Americans in general, the researchers said.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] About half of all US Jews—including those who consider themselves religiously observant—claim in the survey that they have a secular worldview and see no contradiction between that outlook and their faith, according to the study's authors.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Researchers attribute the trends among American Jews to the high rate of intermarriage and "disaffection from Judaism" in the United States.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] American Jews are more likely to be atheists or agnostics than most Americans, especially when they are compared with American Protestants or Catholics.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] A 2003 poll found that while 79% of Americans believe in God, only 48% of American Jews do, compared to 79% and 90% of American Catholics and Protestants respectively.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] While 66% of Americans said that they were "absolutely certain" of God's existence, 24% of American Jews said the same.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] And though 9% of Americans believe that there is no God (8% of American Catholics and 4% of American Protestants), 19% of American Jews believe that God does not exist.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] A 2009 Harris Poll showed that American Jews constitute the one religious group which is most accepting of the science of evolution, with 80% accepting evolution, compared to 51% for Catholics, 32% for Protestants, and 16% of born-again Christians.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] They were also less likely to believe in supernatural phenomena such as miracles, angels, or heaven.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] A 2013 Pew Research Center report found that 1.7 million American Jewish adults, 1.6 million of whom were raised in Jewish homes or had Jewish ancestry, identified as Christians or Messianic Jews but also consider themselves ethnically Jewish.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Another 700,000 American Christian adults considered themselves "Jews by affinity" or "grafted-in" Jews.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] According to a 2020 study by the Pew Research Center, 19% of those who say they were raised Jewish, consider themselves Christian.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] A 2025 Pew Research Center report found that 7% of American adults who identify ethnically as Jewish were raised as Christians.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Additionally, among those who were raised as religious Jews rather than in a Christian environment, 2% now identify as Christian.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Nicknamed *Jubu*s, an increasing number of American Jews have started to adopt Buddhist spiritual practices, while at the same time, they are continuing to identify with and practice Judaism.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] It may be the individual practices both Judaism and Buddhism.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Notable American Jewish Buddhists include: Robert Downey Jr.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Allen Ginsberg, Linda Pritzker, Jonathan F.P.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Rose, Goldie Hawn and daughter Kate Hudson, Steven Seagal, Adam Yauch of the rap group The Beastie Boys, and Garry Shandling.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Film makers the Coen Brothers have been influenced by Buddhism as well for a time.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] A 2025 Pew Research Center report revealed that 1% of American Jewish adults who were raised in Judaism later identified as Muslim.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] In New York City, while the German-Jewish community was well established 'uptown', the more numerous Jews who migrated from Eastern Europe faced tension 'downtown' with Irish and German Catholic neighbors, especially the Irish Catholics who controlled Democratic Party politics at the time.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Jews successfully established themselves in the garment trades and in the needle unions in New York.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] By the 1930s they were a major political factor in New York, with strong support for the most liberal programs of the New Deal.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] They continued as a major element of the New Deal Coalition, giving special support to the Civil Rights Movement.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] By the mid-1960s, however, the Black Power movement caused a growing separation between blacks and Jews, though both groups remained solidly in the Democratic camp.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Earlier Jewish immigrants from Germany tended to be politically conservative, though many, including the devoutly Republican Louis Marshall, believed that Jews should not have a political direction at all.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Meanwhile, the wave of Jews from Eastern Europe starting in the early 1880s were generally more liberal or left-wing and became the political majority.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Many came to America with experience in the socialist, anarchist and communist movements as well as the Labor Bund, emanating from Eastern Europe.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Many Jews rose to leadership positions in the early 20th century American labor movement and helped to found unions that played a major role in left-wing politics and, after 1936, in Democratic Party politics.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] American Jews generally leaned towards the Republican party in the second half of the 19th century and the early years of the 20th century.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] This was compounded by the strong Evangelical imagery used by William Jennings Bryan and other Populist Democrats, which caused fears of Antisemitism among American Jews.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Additionally Republican candidates such as William McKinley and Theodore Roosevelt were extremely popular with Jewish voters.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] However, the majority of Jews have generally voted Democratic since at least 1916, when they voted 55% for Woodrow Wilson, and especially since 1928, when 72% supported the unsuccessful candidacy of Al Smith.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Roosevelt, American Jews voted more solidly Democratic.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] They voted 90% for Roosevelt in the elections of 1940, and 1944, representing the highest of support, equaled only once since.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] In the election of 1948, Jewish support for Democrat Harry S.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Truman dropped to 75%, with 15% supporting the new Progressive Party.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] As a result of lobbying, and hoping to better compete for the Jewish vote, both major party platforms had included a pro-Zionist plank since 1944, and supported the creation of a Jewish state; it had little apparent effect however, with 90% still voting other-than-Republican.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] In every election since, except for 1980, no Democratic presidential candidate has won with less than 67% of the Jewish vote.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] (In 1980, Carter obtained 45% of the Jewish vote.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] During the 1952 and 1956 elections, Jewish voters cast 60% or more of their votes for Democrat Adlai Stevenson, while General Eisenhower garnered 40% of the Jewish vote for his reelection, the best showing to date for the Republicans since Warren G.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Kennedy against Richard Nixon, and in 1964, 90% of American Jews voted for Lyndon Johnson, over his Republican opponent, arch-conservative Barry Goldwater.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Hubert Humphrey garnered 81% of the Jewish vote in the 1968 elections in his losing bid for president against Richard Nixon.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] During the Nixon re-election campaign of 1972, Jewish voters were apprehensive about George McGovern and only favored the Democrat by 65%, while Nixon more than doubled Republican Jewish support to 35%.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] During the Reagan re-election campaign of 1984, the Republican retained 31% of the Jewish vote, while 67% voted for Democrat Walter Mondale.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The 1988 election saw Jewish voters favor Democrat Michael Dukakis by 64%, while George H.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Bush polled a respectable 35%, but during Bush's re-election attempt in 1992, his Jewish support dropped to just 11%, with 80% voting for Bill Clinton and 9% going to independent Ross Perot.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Clinton's re-election campaign in 1996 maintained high Jewish support at 78%, with 16% supporting Bob Dole and 3% for Perot.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] In the 2000 presidential election, Joe Lieberman became the first American Jew to run for national office on a major-party ticket when he was chosen as Democratic presidential candidate Al Gore's vice-presidential nominee.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The elections of 2000 and 2004 saw continued Jewish support for Democrats Al Gore and John Kerry, a Catholic, remain in the high- to mid-70% range, while Republican George W.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Bush's re-election in 2004 saw Jewish support rise from 19% to 24%.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] In the 2008 presidential election, 78% of Jews voted for Barack Obama, who became the first African American to be elected president.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Additionally, 83% of white Jews voted for Obama compared to just 34% of white Protestants and 47% of white Catholics, though 67% of those identifying with another religion and 71% identifying with no religion also voted Obama.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] In the February 2016 New Hampshire Democratic Primary, Bernie Sanders became the first Jewish candidate to win a state's presidential primary election.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] For congressional and senate races, since 1968, American Jews have voted about 70–80% for Democrats; this support increased to 87% for Democratic House candidates during the 2006 elections.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The first American Jew to serve in the Senate was David Levy Yulee, who was Florida's first Senator, serving 1845–1851 and again 1855–1861.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] There were 19 Jews among the 435 US Representatives at the start of the 112th Congress; 26 Democrats and 1 (Eric Cantor) Republican.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] While many of these Members represented coastal cities and suburbs with significant Jewish populations, others did not (for instance, Kim Schrier of Seattle, Washington; John Yarmuth of Louisville, Kentucky; and David Kustoff and Steve Cohen of Memphis, Tennessee).
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The total number of Jews serving in the House of Representatives declined from 31 in the 111th Congress.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] David Cicilline of Rhode Island was the only Jewish American who was newly elected to the 112th Congress; he had been the Mayor of Providence.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The number declined when Jane Harman, Anthony Weiner, and Gabby Giffords resigned during the 112th Congress.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] As of January 2014, there were five openly gay men serving in Congress, and two are Jewish: Jared Polis of Colorado and David Cicilline of Rhode Island.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] In November 2008, Cantor was elected as the House Minority Whip, the first Jewish Republican to be selected for the position.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] In 2011, he became the first Jewish House Majority Leader.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] He served as Majority Leader until 2014, when he resigned shortly after his loss in the Republican primary election for his House seat.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] In 2013, Pew found that 70% of American Jews identified with or leaned toward the Democratic Party, with just 22% identifying with or leaning toward the Republican Party.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The 114th Congress included 10 Jews among 100 U.S.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Senators: nine Democrats (Michael Bennet, Richard Blumenthal, Brian Schatz, Benjamin Cardin, Dianne Feinstein, Jon Ossoff, Jacky Rosen, Charles Schumer, Ron Wyden), and Bernie Sanders, who became a Democrat to run for President but returned to the Senate as an Independent.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] In the 118th Congress, there are 28 Jewish US Representatives.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] 25 are Democrats and the other 3 are Republicans.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Additionally, six members of President Joe Biden's cabinet were Jewish (Secretary of State Antony Blinken, Attorney General Merrick Garland, DNI Avril Haines, White House Chief of Staff Ron Klain, Homeland Security Secretary Alejandro Mayorkas, and Treasury Secretary Janet Yellen).
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] American Jews are a distinctive and influential group in the nation's politics.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Helmreich writes that the ability of American Jews to effect this through political or financial clout is overestimated, that the primary influence lies in the group's voting patterns.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] "Jews have devoted themselves to politics with almost religious fervor," writes Mitchell Bard, who adds that Jews have the highest percentage voter turnout of any ethnic group (84% reported being registered to vote).
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Though the majority (60–70%) of the country's Jews identify as Democratic, Jews span the political spectrum, with those at higher levels of observance being far more likely to vote Republican than their less observant and secular counterparts.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Owing to high Democratic identification in the 2008 United States presidential election, 78% of Jews voted for Democrat Barack Obama versus 21% for Republican John McCain, despite Republican attempts to connect Obama to Muslim and pro-Palestinian causes.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] It has been suggested that running mate Sarah Palin's conservative views on social issues may have nudged Jews away from the McCain–Palin ticket.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] In the 2012 presidential election, 69% of Jews voted for the Democratic incumbent President Obama.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Views of the Democratic and Republican parties were milder: 28% were concerned that Republicans were making alliances with white nationalists and tolerating antisemitism within their ranks, while 27% were concerned that Democrats were tolerating antisemitism within their ranks.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Presidential Election, 77% of American Jews voted for Joe Biden, while 22% voted for Donald Trump.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] A similar trend emerged in the 2024 Presidential Election, where 78% of American Jews voted for Kamala Harris while 22% voted for Donald Trump.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] American Jews across age and gender lines tend to vote for and support politicians and policies which are supported by the Democratic Party.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] On the other hand, Orthodox American Jews have domestic political views which are more similar to those of their religious Christian neighbors.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] American Jews are largely supportive of LGBT rights with 79% responding in a 2011 Pew poll that homosexuality should be "accepted by society", while the overall average in the same 2011 poll among Americans of all demographic groups was that 50%.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] A split on homosexuality exists by level of observance.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Reform rabbis in America perform same-sex marriages as a matter of routine, and there are fifteen LGBT Jewish congregations in North America.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Reform, Reconstructionist and, increasingly, Conservative, Jews are far more supportive on issues like gay marriage than Orthodox Jews are.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] A 2007 survey of Conservative Jewish leaders and activists showed that an overwhelming majority supported gay rabbinical ordination and same-sex marriage.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Accordingly, 78% of Jewish voters rejected Prop 8, the bill that banned gay marriage in California.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] No other ethnic or religious group voted as strongly against it.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] A 2014 Pew poll found that American Jews mostly support abortion rights, with 83% answering that abortion should be legal in all or most cases.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] In considering the trade-off between the economy and environmental protection, American Jews were significantly more likely than other religious groups (excepting Buddhism) to favor stronger environmental protection.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Jews in America also overwhelmingly oppose current United States marijuana policy.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] In 2009, eighty-six percent of Jewish Americans opposed arresting nonviolent marijuana smokers, compared to 61% for the population at large and 68% of all Democrats.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Additionally, 85% of Jews in the United States opposed using federal law enforcement to close patient cooperatives for medical marijuana in states where medical marijuana is legal, compared to 67% of the population at large and 73% of Democrats.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] A 2014 Pew Research survey titled "How Americans Feel About Religious Groups", found that Jews were viewed the most favorably of all other groups, with a rating of 63 out of 100.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Jews were viewed most positively by fellow Jews, followed by white Evangelicals.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Sixty percent of the 3,200 persons surveyed said they had ever met a Jew.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] American Jews have displayed a very strong interest in foreign affairs, especially regarding Germany in the 1930s, and Israel since 1945.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Both major parties have made strong commitments in support of Israel.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Eric Uslaner of the University of Maryland argues, with regard to the 2004 election: "Only 15% of Jews said that Israel was a key voting issue.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] A *New York Times* article suggests that the Jewish movement to the Republican party is focused heavily on faith-based issues, similar to the Catholic vote, which is credited for helping President Bush taking Florida in 2004.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Jewish Americans were more strongly opposed to the Iraq War from its onset than any other ethnic group, or even most Americans.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The greater opposition to the war was not simply a result of high Democratic identification among Jewish Americans, as Jewish Americans of all political persuasions were more likely to oppose the war than non-Jews who shared the same political leanings.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Zionism became a well-organized movement in the U.S. with the involvement of leaders such as Louis Brandeis and the promise of a reconstituted homeland in the Balfour Declaration.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Jewish Americans organized large-scale boycotts of German merchandise during the 1930s to protest Nazi Germany.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Roosevelt's leftist domestic policies received strong Jewish support in the 1930s and 1940s, as did his anti-Nazi foreign policy and his promotion of the United Nations.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The founding of the modern State of Israel in 1948 and recognition thereof by the American government (following objections by American isolationists) was an indication of both its intrinsic support and its response to learning the horrors of the Holocaust.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] This attention was based on a natural affinity toward and support for Israel in the Jewish community.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The attention is also because of the ensuing and unresolved conflicts regarding the founding of Israel and the role for the Zionist movement going forward.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] A lively internal debate commenced, following the Six-Day War.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The American Jewish community was divided over whether or not they agreed with the Israeli response; the great majority came to accept the war as necessary.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Similar tensions were aroused by the 1977 election of Menachem Begin and the rise of Revisionist policies, the 1982 Lebanon War and the continuing administrative governance of portions of the West Bank territory.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Disagreement over Israel's 1993 acceptance of the Oslo Accords caused a further split among American Jews; this mirrored a similar split among Israelis and led to a parallel rift within the pro-Israel lobby, and even ultimately to the United States for its "blind" support of Israel.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Abandoning any pretense of unity, both segments began to develop separate advocacy and lobbying organizations.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The liberal supporters of the Oslo Accord worked through Americans for Peace Now (APN), Israel Policy Forum (IPF) and other groups friendly to the Labour government in Israel.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] They tried to assure Congress that American Jewry was behind the Accord and defended the efforts of the administration to help the fledgling Palestinian Authority (PA), including promises of financial aid.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] In a battle for public opinion, IPF commissioned a number of polls showing widespread support for Oslo among the community.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] In opposition to Oslo, an alliance of conservative groups, such as the Zionist Organization of America (ZOA), Americans For a Safe Israel (AFSI), and the Jewish Institute for National Security Affairs (JINSA) tried to counterbalance the power of the liberal Jews.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Some Zionists also criticized, often in harsh language, Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin and Shimon Peres, his foreign minister and chief architect of the peace accord.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] With the community so strongly divided, AIPAC and the Presidents Conference, which was tasked with representing the national Jewish consensus, struggled to keep the increasingly antagonistic discourse civil.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Reflecting these tensions, Abraham Foxman from the Anti-Defamation League was asked by the conference to apologize for criticizing ZOA's Morton Klein.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The conference, which under its organizational guidelines was in charge of moderating communal discourse, reluctantly censured some Orthodox spokespeople for attacking Colette Avital, the Labor-appointed Israeli Consul General in New York and an ardent supporter of that version of a peace process.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Hate crimes against Jews perpetrated by white supremacists have been increasing due to white supremacy in the United States.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Jews are more than twice as likely to be victims of hate crimes than black or Muslim Americans.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Since the time of the last major wave of Jewish immigration to America (over 2,000,000 Jews from Eastern Europe who arrived between 1890 and 1924), Jewish secular culture in the United States has become integrated in almost every important way with the broader American culture.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Many aspects of Jewish American culture have, in turn, become part of the wider culture of the United States.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Most American Jews today are native English speakers.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] A variety of other languages are still spoken within some American Jewish communities that are representative of the various Jewish ethnic divisions from around the world that have come together to make up all of America's Jewish population.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Many of America's Hasidic Jews, being exclusively of Ashkenazi descent, are raised speaking Yiddish.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Yiddish was once spoken as the primary language by most of the several million Ashkenazi Jews who migrated to the United States.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] It was, in fact, the original language in which *The Forward* was published.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Yiddish has had an influence on American English, and words borrowed from it include *chutzpah* ('effrontery, gall'), *nosh* ('snack'), *schlep* ('drag'), *schmuck* ('an obnoxious, contemptible person', euphemism for 'penis'), and, depending on idiolect, hundreds of other terms.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Many Mizrahi Jews, including those from Arab countries such as Syria, Egypt, Iraq, Yemen, Morocco, Libya, etc. speak Arabic.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] There are communities of Mizrahim in Brooklyn.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The town of Deal, New Jersey, is notably mostly Syrian-Jewish, with many of them Orthodox.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The Persian Jewish community in the United States, notably the large community in and around Los Angeles and Beverly Hills, California, primarily speak Persian (see also Judeo-Persian) in the home and synagogue.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] They also support their own Persian language newspapers.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Persian Jews also reside in eastern parts of New York such as Kew Gardens and Great Neck, Long Island.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Many recent Jewish immigrants from the Soviet Union speak primarily Russian at home, and there are several notable communities where public life and business are carried out mainly in Russian, such as in Brighton Beach in New York City and Sunny Isles Beach in Florida.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] 2010 estimates of the number of Jewish Russian-speaking households in the New York city area are around 92,000, and the number of individuals are somewhere between 223,000 and 350,000.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Another high population of Russian Jews can be found in the Richmond District of San Francisco where Russian markets stand alongside the numerous Asian businesses.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] American Bukharan Jews speak Bukhori, a dialect of Tajik Persian.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] They publish their own newspapers such as the *Bukharian Times* and a large portion live in Queens, New York.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Forest Hills in the New York City borough of Queens is home to 108th Street, which is called by some "Bukharian Broadway", a reference to the many stores and restaurants found on and around the street that have Bukharian influences.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Many Bukharians are also represented in parts of Arizona, Miami, Florida, and areas of Southern California such as San Diego.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] There is a sizeable Mountain Jewish population in Brooklyn, New York, that speaks Judeo-Tat (Juhuri), a dialect of Persian.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Classical Hebrew is the language of most Jewish religious literature, such as the Tanakh (Bible) and Siddur (prayerbook).
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Modern Hebrew is also the primary official language of the modern State of Israel, which further encourages many to learn it as a second language.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Some recent Israeli immigrants to America speak Hebrew as their primary language.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] There are a diversity of Hispanic Jews living in America.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The oldest community is that of the Sephardi Jews of New Netherland.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Their ancestors had fled Spain or Portugal during the Inquisition for the Netherlands, and then came to New Netherland.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Though there is dispute over whether they should be considered Hispanic.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Some Hispanic Jews, particularly in Miami and Los Angeles, immigrated from Latin America.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The largest groups are those that fled Cuba after the communist revolution (known as Jewbans), Argentine Jews, and more recently, Venezuelan Jews.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Argentina is the Latin American country with the largest Jewish population.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] There are a large number of synagogues in the Miami area that give services in Spanish.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The last Hispanic Jewish community would be those that recently came from Portugal or Spain, after Spain and Portugal granted citizenship to the descendants of Jews who fled during the Inquisition.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] All the above listed Hispanic Jewish groups speak either Spanish or Ladino.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Although American Jews have contributed greatly to American arts in general, there still remains a distinctly Jewish American literature.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Jewish American literature often explores the experience of being a Jew in America, and the conflicting pulls of secular society and history.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Yiddish theater was very well attended, and provided a training ground for performers and producers who moved to Hollywood in the 1920s.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Many of the early Hollywood moguls and pioneers were Jewish.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] They played roles in the development of radio and television networks, typified by William S.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Many individual Jews have made significant contributions to American popular culture.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] There have been many Jewish American actors and performers, ranging from early 1900s actors, to classic Hollywood film stars, and culminating in many currently known actors.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The field of American comedy includes many Jews.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The legacy also includes songwriters and authors, for example the author of the song "Viva Las Vegas" Doc Pomus, or *Billy the Kid* composer Aaron Copland.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Many Jews have been at the forefront of women's issues.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The first generation of Jewish Americans who immigrated during the 1880–1924 peak period were not interested in baseball, the country's national pastime, and in some cases tried to prevent their children from watching or participating in baseball-related activities.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Most were focused on making sure they and their children took advantage of education and employment opportunities.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Despite the efforts of parents, Jewish children became interested in baseball quickly since it was already embedded in the broader American culture.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The second generation of immigrants saw baseball as a means to celebrate American culture without abandoning their broader religious community.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] After 1924, many Yiddish newspapers began covering baseball, which they had not done previously.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Since 1845, a total of 34 Jews have served in the Senate, including the 14 present-day senators noted above.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Benjamin was the first practicing Jewish Senator, and would later serve as Confederate Secretary of War and Secretary of State during the Civil War.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Rahm Emanuel served as Chief of Staff to President Barack Obama.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The number of Jews elected to the House rose to an all-time high of 30.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Eight Jews have been appointed to the United States Supreme Court, of which one (Elena Kagan) is currently serving.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Had Merrick Garland's 2016 nomination been accepted, that number would have risen to four out of nine since Ruth Bader Ginsburg and Stephen Breyer were also serving at that time.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The Civil War marked a transition for American Jews.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] It killed off the antisemitic canard, widespread in Europe, to the effect that Jews are cowardly, preferring to run from war rather than serve alongside their fellow citizens in battle.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] At least twenty eight American Jews have been awarded the Medal of Honor.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] More than 550,000 Jews served in the U.S. military during World War II; about 11,000 of them were killed and more than 40,000 of them were wounded.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] There were three recipients of the Medal of Honor; 157 recipients of the Army Distinguished Service Medal, Navy Distinguished Service Medal, Distinguished Service Cross, or Navy Cross; and about 1600 recipients of the Silver Star.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] About 50,000 other decorations and awards were given to Jewish military personnel, making a total of 52,000 decorations.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] During this period, Jews were approximately 3.3 percent of the total U.S. population but they constituted about 4.23 percent of the U.S. armed forces.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] About 60 percent of all Jewish physicians in the United States who were under 45 years of age were in service as military physicians and medics.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Disproportionately many Jewish physicists, such as Richard Feynman, Hans Bethe, John von Neumann as well as the project head, J.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Robert Oppenheimer, were involved in the Manhattan Project, the secret World War II effort to develop the atomic bomb.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Many of these physicists were refugees from Nazi Germany or they were refugees from antisemitic persecution which was also occurring elsewhere in Europe.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Jews have been involved in the American folk music scene since the late 19th century; these tended to be refugees from Central and Eastern Europe, and significantly more economically disadvantaged than their established Western European Sephardic coreligionists.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Historians see it as a legacy of the secular Yiddish theater, cantorial traditions and a desire to assimilate.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] By the 1940s Jews had become established in the American folk music scene.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Guthrie married a Jew and their son Arlo became influential in his own right.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Asch's one-man corporation Folkways Records also released much of the music of Leadbelly and Pete Seeger from the 1940s and 1950s.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Asch's large music catalog was voluntarily donated to the Smithsonian.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Jews have also thrived in jazz music and contributed to its popularization.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Three of the four creators of the Newport Folk Festival, Wein, Bikel and Grossman (Seeger is not) were Jewish.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Albert Grossman put together Peter, Paul and Mary, of which Yarrow is Jewish.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Oscar Brand, from a Canadian Jewish family, has the longest running radio program "Oscar Brand's Folksong Festival" which has been on air consecutively since 1945 from New York City.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] And is the first American broadcast where the host himself will answer any personal correspondence.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The influential group The Weavers, successor to the Almanac Singers, led by Pete Seeger, had a Jewish manager, and two of the four members of the group were Jewish (Gilbert and Hellerman).
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The B-side of "Good Night Irene" had the Hebrew folk song personally chosen for the record by Pete Seeger "Tzena, Tzena, Tzena".
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The influential folk music magazine *Sing Out!* was co-founded and edited by Irwin Silber in 1951, and edited by him until 1967, when the magazine stopped publication for decades.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] *Rolling Stone* magazine's first music critic Jon Landau is of German Jewish descent.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Izzy Young who created the legendary Folklore Center in New York, and currently the Folklore Centrum near Mariatorget in Södermalm, Sweden, which relates to American and Swedish folk music.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Nobel Prize winner Bob Dylan is also Jewish.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Jews have been involved in financial services since the colonial era.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] They received rights to trade fur from the Dutch and Swedish colonies.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] British governors honored these rights after taking over.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] During the Revolutionary War, Haym Solomon helped create America's first semi-central bank, and advised Alexander Hamilton on the building of America's financial system.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] American Jews in the 19th, 20th and 21st centuries played a major role in developing America's financial services industry, both at investment banks and with investment funds.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] German Jewish bankers began to assume a major role in American finance in the 1830s when government and private borrowing to pay for canals, railroads and other internal improvements increased rapidly and significantly.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Men such as August Belmont (Rothschild's agent in New York and a leading Democrat), Philip Speyer, Jacob Schiff (at Kuhn, Loeb & Company), Joseph Seligman, Philip Lehman (of Lehman Brothers), Jules Bache, and Marcus Goldman (of Goldman Sachs) illustrate this financial elite.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] As was true of their non-Jewish counterparts, family, personal, and business connections, a reputation for honesty and integrity, ability, and a willingness to take calculated risks were essential to recruit capital from widely scattered sources.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The families and the firms which they controlled were bound together by religious and social factors, and by the prevalence of intermarriage.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] These personal ties fulfilled real business functions before the advent of institutional organization in the 20th century.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Antisemitic elements often falsely targeted them as key players in a supposed Jewish cabal conspiring to dominate the world.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Since the late 20th century, Jews have played a major role in the hedge fund industry, according to Zuckerman (2009).
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Thus SAC Capital Advisors, Soros Fund Management, Och-Ziff Capital Management, GLG Partners Renaissance Technologies and Elliott Management Corporation are large hedge funds cofounded by Jews.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] They have also played a pivotal role in the private equity industry, co-founding some of the largest firms in the United States, such as Blackstone, Cerberus Capital Management, TPG Capital, BlackRock, Carlyle Group, Warburg Pincus, and KKR.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Very few Jewish lawyers were hired by White Anglo-Saxon Protestant ("WASP") upscale white-shoe law firms, but they started their own.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The WASP dominance in law ended when a number of major Jewish law firms attained elite status in dealing with top-ranked corporations.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] As late as 1950 there was not a single large Jewish law firm in New York City.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] However, by 1965 six of the 20 largest firms were Jewish; by 1980 four of the ten largest were Jewish.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Paul Warburg, one of the leading advocates of the establishment of a central bank in the United States and one of the first governors of the newly established Federal Reserve System, came from a prominent Jewish family in Germany.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Since then, several Jews have served as chairmen of the Fed, including Eugene Meyer (1930-1933), Arthur F.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Many Jews have become remarkably successful as an entrepreneurial and professional minority in the United States.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Many Jewish family businesses that are passed down from one generation to the next serve as an asset, source of income and layer a strong financial groundwork for the family's overall socioeconomic prosperity.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Within the Jewish American cultural sphere, Jewish Americans have also developed a strong culture of entrepreneurship, for excellence in entrepreneurship and engagement in business and commerce is highly prized in Jewish culture.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] American Jews have also been drawn to various disciplines within academia such as physics, sociology, economics, psychology, mathematics, philosophy and linguistics (see Jewish culture for some of the causes), and have played a disproportionate role in numerous academic domains.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Jewish American intellectuals such as Saul Bellow, Ayn Rand, Noam Chomsky, Thomas Friedman, Milton Friedman and Elie Wiesel have made a major impact within mainstream American public life.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Of American Nobel Prize winners, 37 percent have been Jewish Americans (18 times the percentage of Jews in the population), as have been 61 percent of the John Bates Clark Medal in economics recipients (thirty-five times the Jewish percentage).
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] In the business world, it was found in 1995 that while Jewish Americans constituted less than 2.5 percent of the U.S. population, they occupied 7.7 percent of board seats at various U.S. corporations.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] American Jews also have a strong presence in NBA ownership.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Of the 30 teams in the NBA, there are 14 Jewish principal owners.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Several Jews have served as NBA commissioners including prior NBA commissioner David Stern and current commissioner Adam Silver.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Since many careers in science, business, and academia generally pay well, Jewish Americans also tend to have a somewhat higher average income than most Americans.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] The 2000–2001 National Jewish Population Survey shows that the median income of a Jewish family is $54,000 a year ($5,000 more than the average family) and 34% of Jewish households report income over $75,000 a year.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Jewish American people have had a large effect on the cuisine of the United States, with several kosher-style delicatessens achieving mainstream popularity and defining American Jewish culture.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] For that reason, American Jewish food is typically associated with Ashkenazi cuisine, including foods such as bagels, knish, gefilte fish, kreplach, matzoh ball soup, hamantash, lox, kugel, pastrami, and brisket.
[src:laurelton-queens/american-jews-p02] Other Jewish communities, such as the Sephardic community, have influenced the dishes served at American restaurants, particularly in New York City.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka's career spanned nearly 52 years, and his themes range from Black liberation to White racism.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] His notable works of criticism and poetry include "The Music: Reflection on Jazz and Blues", "The Book of Monk", and "New Music, New Poetry", works that draw on topics from the worlds of society, music, and literature.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka's poetry and writing have attracted both high praise and condemnation.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In the African-American community, some compare Baraka to James Baldwin and recognize him as one of the most respected and most widely published Black writers of his generation, though some have said his work is an expression of violence, misogyny, and homophobia.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka was born in Newark, New Jersey, where he attended Barringer High School.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] His father Coyt Leroy Jones worked as a postal supervisor and lift operator.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] His mother Anna Lois (née Russ) was a social worker.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] He wanted to emulate Miles Davis: "I wanted to look like that too—that green shirt and rolled up sleeves on *Milestones* ... always wanted to look like that.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] And be able to play "On Green Dolphin Street" or "Autumn Leaves". ...
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] That's the music you wanted playing when you was coming into a joint, or just looking up at the sky with your baby by your side, that mixture of America and them changes, them blue African magic chants." The influence of jazz can be seen throughout his work later in life.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] He won a scholarship to Rutgers University in 1951 but transferred in 1952 to Howard University.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] His classes in philosophy and religious studies helped lay a foundation for his later writings.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] He subsequently studied at Columbia University and The New School without taking a degree.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In 1954, he joined the United States Air Force as a gunner, reaching the rank of sergeant.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] This was a decision he would come to regret.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] He once explained: "I found out what it was like to be under the direct jurisdiction of people who hated black people.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] I had never known that directly." This experience was yet another that influenced Baraka's later work.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] His commanding officer received an anonymous letter accusing Baraka of being a communist.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] This led to the discovery of Soviet writings in Baraka's possession, his reassignment to gardening duty, and subsequently a dishonorable discharge for violation of his oath of duty.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] He later described his experience in the military as "racist, degrading, and intellectually paralyzing".
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] While he was stationed in Puerto Rico, he worked at the base library, which allowed him ample reading time, and it was here that, inspired by Beat poets back in the mainland US, he began to write poetry.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] The same year, he moved to Greenwich Village, working initially in a warehouse of music records.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] His interest in jazz evolved during this period.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] It was also during this time that he came in contact with the avant-garde Black Mountain poets and New York School poets.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In 1958 he married Hettie Cohen, with whom he had two daughters, Kellie Jones (b.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] He and Hettie founded Totem Press, which published such Beat poets as Jack Kerouac and Allen Ginsberg.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] They also jointly founded a quarterly literary magazine, *Yugen*, which ran for eight issues (1958–1962).
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Through a party that Baraka organized, Ginsberg was introduced to Langston Hughes while Ornette Coleman played saxophone.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka also worked as editor and critic for the literary and arts journal *Kulchur* (1960–65).
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] With Diane di Prima he edited the first twenty-five issues (1961–1963) of their small magazine *The Floating Bear*.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Postal Service seized *The Floating Bear #9*; the FBI charged them for obscenity over William Burroughs' piece "Roosevelt after the Inauguration".
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In the autumn of 1961 he co-founded the New York Poets Theatre with di Prima, the choreographers Fred Herko and James Waring, and the actor Alan S.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] He had an extramarital affair with di Prima for several years; their daughter, Dominique di Prima, was born in June 1962.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka visited Cuba in July 1960 with a Fair Play for Cuba Committee delegation and reported his impressions in his essay "Cuba Libre".
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] There he encountered openly rebellious artists who declared him to be a "cowardly bourgeois individualist" more focused on building his reputation than trying to help those who were enduring oppression.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] This encounter led to a dramatic change in his writing and goals, causing him to become emphatic about supporting black nationalism.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In 1961 Baraka co-authored a "Declaration of Conscience" in support of Fidel Castro's regime.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka also was a member of the Umbra Poets Workshop of emerging Black Nationalist writers (Ishmael Reed and Lorenzo Thomas, among others) on the Lower East Side (1962–1965).
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] His first book of poems, *Preface to a Twenty Volume Suicide Note,* was published in 1961.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka's article "The Myth of a 'Negro Literature'" (1962) stated that "a Negro literature, to be a legitimate product of the Negro experience in America, must get at that experience in exactly the terms America has proposed for it in its most ruthless identity".
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] He also stated in the same work that as an element of American culture, the Negro was entirely misunderstood by Americans.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] As long as black writers were obsessed with being an accepted middle class, Baraka wrote, they would never be able to speak their mind, and that would always lead to failure.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka felt that America only made room for white obfuscators, not black ones.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In 1963 Baraka (under the name LeRoi Jones) published *Blues People: Negro Music in White America*, his account of the development of black music from slavery to contemporary jazz.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] When the work was re-issued in 1999, Baraka wrote in the Introduction that he wished to show that "The music was the score, the actually expressed creative orchestration, reflection of Afro-American life ...
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] That the music was explaining the history as the history was explaining the music.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka (under the name LeRoi Jones) wrote an acclaimed, controversial play titled *Dutchman*, in which a white woman accosts a black man on the New York City Subway.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] The play premiered in 1964 and received the Obie Award for Best American Play in the same year.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] A film of the play, directed by Anthony Harvey, was released in 1967.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] The play has been revived several times, including a 2013 production staged in the East Village.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] After the assassination of Malcolm X in 1965, Baraka changed his name from LeRoi Jones to Amiri Baraka.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] At this time, he also left his wife and their two children and moved to Harlem, where he founded the Black Arts Repertory/Theater School (BARTS) since the Black Arts Movement created a new visual representation of art.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] However, the Black Arts Repertory Theater School remained open for less than a year.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In its short time BARTS attracted many well-known artists, including Sonia Sanchez, Sun Ra and Albert Ayler.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] The Black Arts Repertory Theater School's closure prompted conversation with many other black artists who wanted to create similar institutions.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Consequently, there was a surge in the establishment of these institutions in many places across the United States.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In December 1965 Baraka moved back to Newark after allegations surfaced that he was using federal antipoverty welfare funds for his theater.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka became a leading advocate and theorist for the burgeoning black art during this time.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Now a "black cultural nationalist", he broke away from the predominantly white Beats and became critical of the pacifist and integrationist Civil Rights Movement.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] His revolutionary poetry became more controversial.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] A poem such as "Black Art" (1965), according to Werner Sollors of Harvard University, expressed Baraka's need to commit the violence required to "establish a Black World".
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Rather than use poetry as an escapist mechanism, Baraka saw poetry as a weapon of action.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In April 1965, Baraka's "A Poem for Black Hearts" was published as a direct response to Malcolm X's assassination, and it further exemplifies the poet's uses of poetry to generate anger and endorse rage against oppression.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Like many of his poems, it showed no remorse in its use of raw emotion to convey its message.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] It was published in the September issue of *Negro Digest* and was one of the first responses to Malcolm's death to be exposed to the public.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] The poem is directed particularly at black men, and it scoldingly labels them "faggots" in order to challenge them to act and continue the fallen activist's fight against the white establishment.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka also promoted theatre as a training for the "real revolution" yet to come, with the arts being a way to forecast the future as he saw it.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In "The Revolutionary Theatre", Baraka wrote, "We will scream and cry, murder, run through the streets in agony, if it means some soul will be moved." In opposition to the peaceful protests inspired by Martin Luther King Jr., Baraka believed that a physical uprising must follow the literary one.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka's decision to leave Greenwich Village in 1965 was an outgrowth of his response to the debate about the future of black liberation.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In 1966, Baraka married his second wife, Sylvia Robinson, who later adopted the name Amina Baraka.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] The two would open a facility in Newark known as Spirit House, a combination playhouse and artists' residence.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In 1967, he lectured at San Francisco State University.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] The year after, he was arrested in Newark for having allegedly carried an illegal weapon and resisting arrest during the 1967 Newark riots.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] He was subsequently sentenced to three years in prison.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] His poem "Black People", published in the *Evergreen Review* in December 1967, was read by the judge in court, including the phrase: "All the stores will open if you say the magic words.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] The magic words are: "Up against the wall motherfucker this is a stick up!" Shortly afterward an appeals court reversed the sentence based on his defense by attorney Raymond A.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] He later joked that he was charged with holding "two revolvers and two poems".
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] That same year his second book of jazz criticism, *Black Music*, came out.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] It was a collection of previously published music journalism, including the seminal *Apple Cores* columns from *Down Beat* magazine.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In 1967, Baraka (still LeRoi Jones) visited Maulana Karenga in Los Angeles and became an advocate of his philosophy of Kawaida, a multifaceted, categorized activist philosophy that produced the "Nguzo Saba", Kwanzaa, and an emphasis on African names.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] It was at this time that he adopted the name *Imamu Amear Baraka*.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] *Imamu* is a Swahili title for "spiritual leader", derived from the Arabic word *Imam* (إمام).
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] According to Shaw, he dropped the honorific *Imamu* and eventually changed *Amear* (which means "Prince") to *Amiri*.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] *Baraka* means "blessing, in the sense of divine favor".
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Gibson's candidacy for mayor of Newark; Gibson was elected as the city's first African-American mayor.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In the late 1960s and early 1970s, Baraka courted controversy by penning some strongly anti-Jewish poems and articles.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Historian Melani McAlister points to an example of this writing: "In the case of Baraka, and in many of the pronouncements of the NOI [Nation of Islam], there is a profound difference, both qualitative and quantitative, in the ways that white ethnicities were targeted.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Prior to this time, Baraka prided himself on being a forceful advocate of Black cultural nationalism; however, by the mid-1970s, he began finding its racial individuality confining.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka's separation from the Black Arts Movement began because he saw certain Black writers – capitulationists, as he called them – countering the Black Arts Movement that he created.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] He believed that the groundbreakers in the Black Arts Movement were doing something that was new, needed, useful, and Black, and those who did not want to see a promotion of black expression were "appointed" to the scene to damage the movement.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In 1974, Baraka distanced himself from Black nationalism, embracing Marxism–Leninism in the context of Maoist third-world liberation movements.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In 1979, he became a lecturer in the State University of New York at Stony Brook's Africana Studies Department in the College of Arts and Sciences at the behest of faculty member Leslie Owens.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Articles about Baraka appeared in the university's print media from *Stony Brook Press*, *Blackworld*, and other student campus publications.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] These articles included a page-one exposé of his positions in the inaugural issue of *Stony Brook Press* on October 25, 1979, discussing his protests "against what he perceived as racism in the Africana Studies Department, as evidenced by a dearth of tenured professors".
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Shortly thereafter, Baraka took a tenure-track assistant professorship at Stony Brook in 1980 to assist "the struggling Africana Studies Department"; in 1983, he was promoted to associate professor and earned tenure.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In June 1979 Baraka was arrested and jailed at Eighth Street and Fifth Avenue in Manhattan.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Different accounts emerged around the arrest, yet all sides agreed that Baraka and his wife, Amina, were in their car arguing over the cost of their children's shoes.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] The police version of events holds that they were called to the scene after a report of an assault in progress.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] They maintain that Baraka was hitting his wife, and when they moved to intervene, he attacked them as well, whereupon they used the necessary force to subdue him.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Amina's account contrasted with that of the police; she held a news conference the day after the arrest accusing the police of lying.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] A grand jury dismissed the assault charge, but the resisting arrest charge moved forward.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In November 1979 after a seven-day trial, a criminal court jury found Baraka guilty of resisting arrest.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] A month later he was sentenced to 90 days at Rikers Island (the maximum he could have been sentenced to was one year).
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Amina declared that her husband was "a political prisoner".
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka was released after a day in custody pending his appeal.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] At the time it was noted that if he was kept in prison, "he would be unable to attend a reception at the White House in honor of American poets." Baraka's appeal continued up to the State Supreme Court.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] During the process, his lawyer, William M.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Kunstler, told the press that Baraka "feels it's the responsibility of the writers of America to support him across the board".
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Backing for his attempts to have the sentence canceled or reduced came from "letters of support from elected officials, artists and teachers around the country".
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] The judge noted that having Baraka serve his 90 days on weekends would allow him to continue his teaching obligations at Stony Brook.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Rather than serve his sentence at the prison, Baraka was allowed to serve his 48 consecutive weekends in a Harlem halfway house.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] While serving his sentence he wrote *The Autobiography*, tracing his life from birth to his conversion to socialism.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] During the 1982–83 academic year, Baraka returned to Columbia University as a visiting professor, teaching a course entitled "Black Women and Their Fictions".
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] After becoming a full professor of African Studies at Stony Brook in 1985, Baraka took an indefinite visiting appointment in Rutgers University's English department in 1988; over the next two years, he taught a number of courses in African American literature and music.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka would go on to collectively liken the committee to an "Ivy League Goebbels" while also characterizing the senior faculty as "powerful Klansmen", leading to a condemnation from department chair Barry Qualls.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Thereafter, Baraka was nominally affiliated with Stony Brook as professor emeritus of Africana Studies until his death.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In 1987, together with Maya Angelou and Toni Morrison, he was a speaker at the commemoration ceremony for James Baldwin.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In 1989 Baraka won an American Book Award for his works as well as a Langston Hughes Award.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In 1990 he co-authored the autobiography of Quincy Jones, and in 1998 he appeared in a supporting role in Warren Beatty's film *Bulworth*.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In 1996, Baraka contributed to the AIDS benefit album *Offbeat: A Red Hot Soundtrip* produced by the Red Hot Organization.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In July 2002, Baraka was named Poet Laureate of New Jersey by Governor Jim McGreevey.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] The position was to be for two years and came with a $10,000 stipend.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka held the post for a year, during which time he was mired in controversy, including substantial political pressure and public outrage demanding his resignation.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Dodge Poetry Festival in Stanhope, New Jersey, Baraka read his 2001 poem on the September 11th attacks "Somebody Blew Up America?", which was criticized for antisemitism and attacks on public figures.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Because there was no mechanism in the law to remove Baraka from the post, and he refused to step down, the position of state poet laureate was officially abolished by the State Legislature and Governor McGreevey.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In October 2002, 131 creatives and activists signed the surrealist-sponsored declaration "Poetry Matters: On the Media Persecution of Amiri Baraka" in solidarity with him.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In 2002, scholar Molefi Kete Asante included Baraka on his list of *100 Greatest African Americans*.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka collaborated with hip-hop group The Roots on the song "Something in the Way of Things (In Town)" on their 2002 album *Phrenology*.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In 2003, Baraka's daughter Shani, aged 31, and her lesbian partner, Rayshon Homes, were murdered in the home of Shani's sister, Wanda Wilson Pasha, by Pasha's ex-husband, James Coleman.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Prosecutors argued that Coleman shot Shani because she had helped her sister separate from her husband.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] A New Jersey jury found Coleman (also known as Ibn El-Amin Pasha) guilty of murdering Shani Baraka and Rayshon Holmes, and he was sentenced to 168 years in prison for the 2003 shooting.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka (born 1970), is a politician and activist in Newark, who served as principal of Newark's Central High School, as an elected member of the Municipal Council of Newark (2002–06, 2010–present) representing the South Ward.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka became Mayor of Newark on July 1, 2014.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Amiri Baraka died on January 9, 2014, at Beth Israel Medical Center in Newark, New Jersey, after being hospitalized in the facility's intensive care unit for one month before his death.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] The cause of death was not reported initially, but it is mentioned that Baraka had a long struggle with diabetes.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Later reports indicated that he died from complications after a recent surgery.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka's funeral was held at Newark Symphony Hall on January 18, 2014.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka's work has been criticized for being racist, homophobic, antisemitic and misogynist among others.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka and his writings emanated extreme and hostile anti-white sentiment.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] He viewed blacks as morally superior than whites, whom he believed were innately evil.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka advocated for the rape of white women by Black men, believing that it was a politically legitimate act.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka objectified white women, believing that they served as a location of racial struggle rather than as human beings.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] He implied that white women would enjoy being raped by Black men, experiencing the rape as "sexually exhilarating—a God-like gift that no white man could give to her".
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] If she did not, and she instead perceived her rape by a Black man as a "beast-like violation", then she was racist.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka frequently denounced homosexuality in his writing.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] He employed homophobic slurs in his writings (e.g. faggot), usually against white men, but also against black men he disagreed with.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Some critics have alleged Baraka's homophobia to be suppressed homosexual desire.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In the 1967 poem "The Black Man is Making New Gods", Baraka accused Jews of having stolen knowledge of Africa, transporting it to Europe, where they became white and claimed it as their own.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] He wrote of Jesus as a "fag" and as "the dead jew" who, Baraka argues, was a Jewish scam on Christians.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka embraces Nazi genocidal depictions of Jews, who embody a "dangerous germ culture".
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] His 1972 essay collection *Raise, Race, Rays, Raze* refers to people as "jew-slick", "jeworiented revolutionaries", and also "cohen edited negro history".
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In 1980 Baraka published an essay in the *Village Voice* that was titled *Confessions of a Former Anti-Semite*.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka insisted that a *Village Voice* editor titled it and not himself.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In the essay, Baraka went over his life history, including his marriage to Hettie Cohen, who was Jewish.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] He stated that after the assassination of Malcolm X, he found himself thinking: "As a Black man married to a white woman, I began to feel estranged from her ...
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] How could someone be married to the enemy?" He eventually divorced Hettie and left her with their two bi-racial daughters.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In July 2002, ten months after the September 11 attacks on the World Trade Center, Baraka wrote a poem entitled "Somebody Blew Up America?" that was accused of antisemitism and met with harsh criticism.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] The poem is highly critical of racism in America, and includes humorous depictions of public figures such as Trent Lott, Clarence Thomas, and Condoleezza Rice.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka said that he believed Israelis and President George W.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Bush had advance knowledge of the September 11 attacks, citing what he described as information that had been reported in the American and Israeli press and on Jordanian television.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka himself denied that the poem is antisemitic, due to the use of word "Israeli" rather than "Jew".
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] However, antisemitism watchdog organizations such as the Anti-Defamation League (ADL) denounced the poem as antisemitic.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] The ADL noted that the "4000 workers" conspiracy theory had initially referred to Jews in general and claimed that Baraka was using an antisemitic tactic of replacing references to Jews at large with references to Israel and then claiming a comment is merely anti-Zionist.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] After the poem's publication, Governor Jim McGreevey tried to remove Baraka from the post of Poet Laureate of New Jersey, to which he had been appointed in July 2002.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] McGreevey learned that there was no legal way, according to the law authorizing and defining the position, to remove Baraka.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] On October 17, 2002, legislation to abolish the post was introduced in the State Senate and subsequently signed by McGreevey, becoming effective July 2, 2003.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] The poet laureate post ceased to exist when the law became effective.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In response to legal action filed by Baraka, the United States Court of Appeals for the Third Circuit ruled that state officials were immune from such suits, and in November 2007 the Supreme Court of the United States refused to hear an appeal of the case.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka served as the second Poet Laureate of New Jersey from July 2002 until the position was abolished on July 2, 2003.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In response to the attempts to remove Baraka as the state's Poet Laureate, a nine-member advisory board named him the poet laureate of the Newark Public Schools in December 2002.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] A short excerpt from Amiri Baraka's poetry was selected to be used for a permanent installation by artist Larry Kirkland in New York City's Pennsylvania Station.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Despite numerous controversies and polarizing content of his work, Baraka's literary influence is undeniable.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] His co-founding of the Black Arts Movement in the 1960s promoted a uniquely black nationalist perspective and influenced an entire literary generation.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Critic Naila Keleta-Mae argues that Baraka's legacy is one of "saying the unsayable", a course that likely damaged his own literary reputation and canonization.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] For example, Baraka was left out of the 2013 anthology *Angles of Ascent*, a collection of contemporary African-American poetry published by Norton.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] In a review of the anthology, Baraka criticized editor Charles H.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Rowell's hostility towards the Black Arts Movement, calling Rowell's "attempt to analyze and even compartmentalize" contemporary African-American poetry as "flawed".
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Indeed, Rowell's introduction to *Angles of Ascent* references the "fetters of narrow political and social demands that have nothing to do with the production of artistic texts", evincing a political/apolitical dichotomy where the editor considers overly political works of lesser artistic value.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka's participation in a diverse array of artistic genres combined with his own social activism allowed him to have a wide range of influence.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] When discussing his influence in an interview with NPR, Baraka stressed that he had influenced numerous people.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] When asked what he would write for his own epitaph, he quipped, "We don't know if he ever died", evincing the personal importance of his own legacy to him.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] NPR's obituary for Baraka describes the depths of his influence simply: "...throughout his life – the Black Arts Movement never stopped".
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] Baraka's influence also extends to the publishing world, where some writers credit him with opening doors to white publishing houses which African American writers previously had been unable to access.
[src:laurelton-queens/amiri-baraka] For the 60th anniversary of Baraka's *Blues People*, trumpeter and composer Russell Gunn premiered a suite, *The Blues and Its People*, inspired by it at the Apollo.
[src:laurelton-queens/area-code-917] In 1984, the numbering plan area was divided by splitting Brooklyn, Queens, and Staten Island into a separate numbering plan area with area code 718, reducing 212 to only Manhattan and the Bronx.
[src:laurelton-queens/area-code-917] In 1990, the New York Telephone Company wanted to assign a new area code, 917, to all cellphones and pagers in Manhattan and all telephone lines in the Bronx, to relieve number shortages in Manhattan, but the New York Public Service Commission denied the request.
[src:laurelton-queens/area-code-917] The restriction to mobile services was ruled impermissible by the Federal Communications Commission (FCC) which grandfathered that use in New York City.
[src:laurelton-queens/area-code-917] Instead, in 1992, area code 212 was restricted for use in Manhattan only.
[src:laurelton-queens/area-code-917] The Bronx, along with the small exchange area of Marble Hill, was integrated into 718.
[src:laurelton-queens/area-code-917] All boroughs were provided with the additional area code 917, arranged in an overlay complex.
[src:laurelton-queens/area-code-917] Introduced on February 4, 1992, area code 917 was the first overlay area code in the North American Numbering Plan.
[src:laurelton-queens/area-code-917] When it was established, all cellphones in New York City were switched to 917, freeing up telephone numbers for additional landlines.
[src:laurelton-queens/area-code-917] Shortly after the establishment of the 917 code, the FCC ruled that restriction of area codes to particular types of service was prohibited, but the instance of 917 remained exempt.
[src:laurelton-queens/laurelton-queens] Laurelton is located in Queens Community District 13; its ZIP Codes are 11413 and 11422.
[src:laurelton-queens/laurelton-queens] It is patrolled by the New York City Police Department's 105th Precinct.
[src:laurelton-queens/laurelton-queens] Laurelton derives its name from the Laurelton station on the Long Island Rail Road, which was named for the laurels that grew there over 100 years ago.
[src:laurelton-queens/laurelton-queens] It was developed by Dean Alvord and was modeled after an English village, with stately Tudor-style homes, both attached and detached.
[src:laurelton-queens/laurelton-queens] A few co-ops exist in a former garden apartment complex, there has been some new construction but no high-rise buildings, which has enabled Laurelton to keep its small-town feel.
[src:laurelton-queens/laurelton-queens] The area of Laurelton closest to Rosedale and Cambria Heights consists primarily of single-family homes whereas the area abutting Springfield Gardens contains more multi-family homes.
[src:laurelton-queens/laurelton-queens] The area south of Merrick Boulevard contains many large, individually designed houses, while certain blocks to the north, running eastward from Francis Lewis Boulevard, have attached, Tudor-style rowhouses.
[src:laurelton-queens/laurelton-queens] Laurelton also has a series of streets with landscaped and tree-lined center malls.
[src:laurelton-queens/laurelton-queens] Based on data from the 2010 United States census, the population of Laurelton was 24,453, a decrease of 1,922 (7.3%) from the 26,375 in 2000.
[src:laurelton-queens/laurelton-queens] Covering an area of 909.17 acres (367.93 ha), the neighborhood had a population density of 26.9 inhabitants per acre (17,200/sq mi; 6,600/km2).
[src:laurelton-queens/laurelton-queens] Hispanic or Latino of any race were 5.5% (1,344) of the population.
[src:laurelton-queens/laurelton-queens] Belt Parkway exits 24A/B, 23A, and 22 service Laurelton.
[src:laurelton-queens/laurelton-queens] The section of the Belt Parkway known as the Laurelton Parkway was the subject of a master plan as part of the city's emerging system of greenways and bikeways.
[src:laurelton-queens/laurelton-queens] The restoration of this 1.5 miles (2.4 km) link was completed in 2006.
[src:laurelton-queens/laurelton-queens] The Laurelton station on the Long Island Rail Road, located at 225th Street and 141st Road, offers service via the Far Rockaway and Long Beach branches.
[src:laurelton-queens/laurelton-queens] Residents also have access to MTA Regional Bus Operations buses Q5, Q77, Q84, Q85, Q86, Q87 and Q89, which connect to New York City Subway stops in Jamaica.
[src:laurelton-queens/laurelton-queens] The QM63 and QM65 express buses to Manhattan also stops in Laurelton.
